&quot;The Making of a Mage&quot; (4 stories). The Making of a Mage can be found elsewhere on this board.<br>
<br>
The sun burned hotly above the many people waiting in the lineup.  Raff wiped his forehead with the back of his shirtsleeve and shifted wordlessly.  He'd been in line now for over 3 hours, but at least he was nearing the front.  After two more people it would be his turn.  He placed his large wooden staff firmly on the ground and leaned on it.  I'm too old for this he thought to himself as he looked around at the others waiting patiently in line.  His face had a slightly leathery appearance, but overall he didn't look anything near his age.  At 35 he'd seen more than his share of the world, and during the last few years, his lifestyle had extracted a great toll from him, but there was a spark of life in his eyes that made most people think he'd just spent too many years in the desserts of Ro where the wind swept sand turned a boys face to a man's in a few years.   When he moved it was the motion of an older man - a careful confident movement that suggested his body had been everywhere before.  The unaware would think they were dealing with a man well into his 40's until they saw his eyes.  When they did, they knew there was much more to this man than they expected.  Raff had the kind of eyes that warned fools off, deterred would-be swindlers, and forced thieves to consider easier targets.  Now he turned those eyes on the young men and women around him.<br>
<br>
Ahead of him were two young boys, both blonde haired blue eyed.  They shifted excitedly, occasionally looking around as if they didn't belong here in the Academy of Arcane Science.  The first boy was answering questions quietly, his voice breaking occasionally in nervousness.  There were four representatives questioning him, asking him about various things including his parentage, his skills in other areas, and his motivations for wanting to join the guild.  Raff watched detachedly as the boy nodded his head and bowed, barely concealing his excitement.  It appeared, from the boy's reaction, as if he'd been accepted.  A moment later the boy left, flashing a quick smile to his twin. <br>
<br>
Raff and the boy in front of him waited patiently as the four men at the table discussed amongst themselves.  A short while later one of them, a gnome, turned to the boy and asked him to step forward.  Raff moved forward, taking the boy’s place and leaned once again on his staff.  As he waited he considered what he was about to do.<br>
<br>
After four years of alcohol-induced gambling, fighting and whoring he was finally going to do something with his life.  The pain of his wife's death still burned deeply in his heart, and he knew he'd never be completely rid of it, but he felt the time had come for him to find a way to go on with his life.  He wasn't doing it for himself because, truthfully, he didn't give a damn about his life.  Instead he was going to make something of his life because he knew that Glorias would be furious with him if he didn't.  Even dead his wife was a source of motivation for him.  Besides, he thought, if Erollisi ever found her way to see the two of them reunited he'd have a lot of explaining to do, and, even in death, he didn't relish explaining to his wife how he'd managed to waste the years of his life following her death.  And so, magician school was his ticket to a new life.<br>
<br>
Raff looked past the balcony he was standing on and gazed at the water below.  He slowly ran two fingers along his thick moustache and sighed.  This is the right thing to do he said to himself reassuringly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Excuse me?&quot; a voice shocked Raff out of his thoughts.  He turned to the speaker and blinked.<br>
<br>
The four men behind the large wooden table were all looking at him.  The gnome who had spoken to him has a bemused look on his face.<br>
<br>
&quot;Were you applying for the janitor position?&quot; the gnome said.  The four men laughed loudly at the remark and glanced knowingly amongst themselves.  The gnome put his hands behind his head casually and leaned back in his chair.  In spite of himself, Raff felt his face flushing.<br>
<br>
&quot;Pardon me.&quot; He spoke carefully. &quot;I was lost in thought.&quot;  Raff bowed stiffly and tried to compose himself.<br>
<br>
&quot;And what can we do for you&quot; said an older brown haired man at the end of the table.  He still wore a large smile from the previous joke.  &quot;If it's not for the janitor's position, then what are you here for?”<br>
<br>
Raff cleared his throat and spoke carefully.  &quot;I wish to apply for entrance into the Academy of Arcane Science.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, I see.&quot; Said the gnome, his hands still behind his head. &quot;And what is it that makes you think we'd be interested in someone as old as you?&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff licked his lips. He was prepared for this.  &quot;I believe that the school judges people on their abilities and not on their age.  In fact, the older a magician is, the more powerful they become.&quot;<br>
<br>
The gnome pointed a tiny finger at Raff and leaned forward. &quot;Old magicians are powerful because they started young Raff.  Look around you. Do you see any other old applicants?  There's a reason for that.  You can't learn all the subtleties of our art in a few years. It takes a lifetime.&quot;<br>
<br>
The other three men nodded in silent agreement.<br>
<br>
Raff nodded at the men before him.  &quot;I understand that, and I know my path will be a hard one, but I've considered this at great length and I firmly believe it is the path for me.  I simply must work harder than the younger students to make up for lost time. However, I will have experience as an advantage. I know much more about life and it's struggles than any younger pupil. I'm no stranger to hard work, to trials and tribulations, or to failure. I know these things all too well.&quot;  He bowed his head solemnly. &quot;And I will do what must be done to be successful.&quot;<br>
<br>
The gnome leaned forward, clasping his hands together and leaning on the table.  &quot;Raff,&quot; he said quietly. &quot;We know all about your experience.&quot;  He spoke as if he didn't want to have the words in his mouth too long lest they foul him with their taint.  He glared at Raff and hissed, &quot;Your experience with whores and vodka won't do you any good in my school, and we won't have you or your kind taking the position of a younger, better, honest and more capable student.&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff's head snapped up and his eyes widened at the gnome’s words.  The tiny magician narrowed his eyes and leaned back into his chair slowly.  Raff blinked and turned his head slowly to the others.  The brown haired man looked embarrassed and held out a hand as if to calm everyone.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Look,&quot; he said slowly. &quot;I don't think this has to become nasty.&quot;  He looked up at Raff.  &quot;Raff, I'm afraid I have to agree with Dooly.  Your reputation does precede you.  Surely you had thought about this?&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff opened his mouth and stood in stunned speechlessness.  His mouth worked as if he was about to talk, but he couldn't find the words.<br>
<br>
&quot;Raff,&quot; began a middle-aged man as he looked between Dooly and Raff.  &quot;The School has a certain reputation to uphold.  We have to consider what allowing you in would do to our status among the other guilds in the Academy.  You must understand that.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What must I do to prove myself then&quot; Raff spoke, his voice barely audible.  &quot;Surely you must understand my behavior over the last few years was a reaction to my wife's death at the hands of the orcs.&quot;  There was no response from the men at the table.  He leaned forward and spoke quietly, his voice tight with anger.  &quot;You can't do this to me! I've finally taken the steps to improve my life.  Look at me!  I'm not the same man I was a month ago!  You cannot deny that!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That's true Raff, but...&quot; began the brown haired man.<br>
<br>
&quot;Fine Raff.&quot; Interrupted Dooly.  &quot;You're not the same man now.  How long will it be before you revert to that man?  How long before the stress of training causes you to break and once again go on a drunken spree of thieving and whoring?  Or, Brell forbid, what happens when you snap once we have taught you some of our secrets and use them in your rage?  What then Raff?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Then you will deal with me as you would any other student. I would be punished, perhaps expelled.  But until that happens, you have no right to refuse...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Enough!&quot; Dooly slammed his small hand down upon the table.  &quot;You will not be a member of the magician's guild.  Begone!&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff started in surprise.  He looked at the other three men carefully.  None would look at him.  Slowly he turned his gaze toward Dooly who had once again leaned back in his chair casually.  Raff trembled slightly with the anger building within him and leaned forward with deliberate slowness until he was mere inches from Dooly's face.  His hands gripped the edge of the table and he glared at the gnome. Dooly returned the fiery gaze with his own, but he was unprepared for what he saw.  In Raff's eyes he saw the smoldering fury of a man who would stop at nothing to seek vengeance.  The gnome knew such a man was dangerous and he swallowed slowly in spite of himself and prepared himself for a blow.  For a moment everything was silent.  The people waiting in line who had been chatting stopped.  Those with a gift for magic could feel Dooly drawing upon his magical energies.  <br>
<br>
Then Raff said quietly &quot;I suppose we'll see about that.&quot;  With those words he stood, turned and strode away quickly.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
