<br>
Raff had heard many times how the depths of Neriak were dark, but he was unprepared for the utter blackness around him.  He waited just inside the entrance for his heart to slow down and his eyes to adjust to the change in lighting, but it was useless. Long after his heart had slowed he still couldn't see a thing.  He had prepared for such an event, and fumbled around in his backpack searching for one of the torches he'd brought with him.  Once he had one in hand, he retrieved a tinderbox and lit it.  The weak light of the torch was like a bonfire in the thick darkness, casting flickering shadows along the smooth walls and by its light Raff noticed he was not alone.   Not far from him, resting on the floor, two Dark Elves were speaking with each other quietly.  As he walked past them he noticed with some relief that they didn't seem concerned enough to even lift their heads.  <br>
<br>
Good he thought.  They don't see me as a threat.  It was true of course; Raff wasn't a threat.  A single human in the underground city of the Dark Elves couldn't possibly be a threat.  In fact, Raff was the one feeling threatened, and with good reason.  He knew all too well the stories about what the Dark Elves did to intruders.  He turned and looked back at where he'd entered Neriak and noticed with some concern that even though he'd progressed only a dozen feet or so, the entrance was completely enshrouded in darkness.  He turned his head forward and continued on.<br>
<br>
His progress was slow and often he had to stop and bring his torch close to the ground so he could see the floor beneath him.  He knew of the dangerous drop offs and sheer precipices found in Neriak, knowledge that forced him to proceed carefully.  In the distance he could make out a strange red and blue glowing object.  He saw no better destination, so he continued his slow pace toward the object.  <br>
<br>
He began to think, not for the last time, that his judgment was impaired when he chose to come to this place.  For the hundredth time in the last day he considered his plans.  After the way the Academy of Arcane Science rejected him, he felt he didn't have many choices left.  So.  According to the Academy he was no good for them; he wasn't the type of person they needed in their school.  Fine.  Raff wasn't about to give up.  He had been through his options as many times as he could, and there weren't any alternatives.  At least no good alternatives.  He had to do something with his life, and he wasn't about to return to the life of scraping and saving for years to build an inn.  He was too old to start over.  What he needed was something lucrative - something he could make a living off of now, not ten years from now.  And, there was no doubt in his mind that danger was something he wanted.  As far as he was concerned, his life was barely worth living.  In fact, the only reason he had to go on was the memory of Glorias, and how she'd react when he met her again.  He didn't relish explaining to his beautiful wife how he'd wasted 40 years of his life because he was feeling sorry for himself.  He sighed heavily as he trudged along.<br>
<br>
He was nearing the glowing object when his torch burned out.  The red and blue glow played eerily along the walls giving them a magical look.  He rummaged through his pack to find another torch, silently cursing himself for not watching the first one more carefully.  Hopefully this is the last day I need to light a torch he thought as he cursed quietly.  The strange lights made it difficult to find anything in his pack; they were bright enough to confuse his human eyes, yet weak enough that they didn't help him discern anything.  Finally, after much feeling around in his pack, he retrieved a fresh torch, lit it, and stood up, slinging his pack back onto his shoulder.  He held the torch high and tried to make out his surroundings.<br>
<br>
From the little he could see, he thought he was standing on a bridge.  He heard the faint sound of running water, but there was no way to tell how high above that water he was.  He swung the torch around, trying to see more, but his eyes were denied so he continued toward the glowing symbol.  The walkway he was on sloped upward and he soon realized he would pass underneath the glowing object.  He stopped and looked at it a moment, holding the torch away from his eyes so that it's light didn't interfere with the object's magical glow.  After a futile attempt to comprehend the object's meaning he decided it must be a Dark Elf symbol of some type.  He brought his torch back toward his body, turned his head back to where he was headed, and froze.  Less than 10 feet away from him were two Dragoons.  They weren't moving, but their mere presence drove a dagger of fear into Raff's chest.  He willed himself to breathe, slowly working air into his lungs.  The guards didn't seem to notice him, but he couldn't escape the feeling that they were somehow laughing at his fear.  He swallowed and forced himself to look past them.  About 20 feet behind the guards there was a large metal gate.  He walked up to it cautiously, somehow finding the strength of will to force his feet to move past the ominous guards.  He found the mechanism that raised the portcullis and pulled on it.  It moved with remarkable ease, and the gate lifted into the surrounding rock with a dark metallic clanking, driven by some unseen force.  Raff looked to his side and noticed with great relief that the guards were still ignoring him.  He continued on.<br>
<br>
The glow produced by the strange object quickly faded as he walked deeper into the subterranean city, and a few footsteps later he was once again straining to see his surroundings.  From the information he was able to gather, he thought the commons should be nearby.  There he would find illumination sufficient for his human eyes, because the commons was home to many races, including humans. A short while later his prediction was confirmed when the sounds of busy people floated down the passageway.   A long passage and three turns later he could see the glow he was looking for.  The random flicker of light shed from torches and lanterns danced along the walls of the cavern ahead of him.  He rallied his nerves and strode into the open commons area in a manner he hoped looked confident.<br>
<br>
The cavern was enormous; the ceiling vaulted high above Raff's head and disappeared in the obscurity of darkness.  All around him there were shops, street vendors, and taverns.  People of all races, from human to gnome bustled around moving from merchant to merchant, all intent on their own business.  The dull hum of hundreds of voices mixed easily with the chaotic jumble of smells from bakeries, taverns, leather shops, and smithies. If it wasn't for the deep darkness surrounding them it could easily be an ordinary scene from Freeport.  Raff thought this might be what Freeport would look like if its people were nocturnal. As he looked around his stomach grumbled in protest of the smells surrounding him and he realized he hadn't eaten since he woke up 5 hours earlier.  Cautiously he placed a hand firmly on his belt pouch and checked to make sure his knife was within easy reach.  Years of living on the streets of Freeport had taught him well..<br>
<br>
&quot;Get out of the way, ya daft bugger!&quot;  Raff felt a hand on his back and was roughly shoved forward as a group of humans moved past him, intent on quenching their thirst at a nearby tavern.  Moments later he was bumped to the side by a Dwarf wearing a gleaming blue set of full plate armour as the powerful warrior walked past. He was quickly shoved back by another and then another until he was pressed against the wall of the cavern.  Resolutely he began working his way through the sea of people to the opposite side from where he'd entered the commons area.  The process was slow, and he had to pause more than once to allow people to squeeze past him before continuing on.<br>
<br>
After he crossed the open market square he stopped to determine where he was.  He unrolled a small map from inside his pack and examined it briefly.  He figured the mages guild was nearby, and began walking in its direction, rolling up his map as he went.  From what he knew of the Dark Elves, they would accept him into their guild as long as he was willing to do what was necessary.  He was grimly aware that he might not want to do everything they requested, but was absolutely resolute to do whatever it took to secure a position within the guild.  Visions of horrible requests had filled his head over the last few days, but regardless of the cost,  he had decided he was going to be a mage.  He would not let Glorias down; he would do something with his life.  It really didn't matter to Raff anyway. As far as he was concerned, his life was worthless, and there was nothing anyone could take away from him that hadn't been taken long ago.<br>
<br>
He found the ramp leading up to the mages guild and walked up it, his torch held above his head.  The light here was less than in the commons area, but still much greater than the utter blackness before the commons.  As he reached the top of the ramp, he noticed an iron gate blocking his way.  This time there were no Dragoons standing beside it.  He took a deep breath and reached out to pull down the lever that worked the gate.  Again the gate disappeared into the ceiling effortlessly, this time with the dry rumble of stone on stone.  Raff found himself wondering if every gate had it's own unique sound.  He walked into the room beyond the gate thrusting his torch ahead of him.  <br>
<br>
As he moved forward he heard the unmistakable sound of a magic spell being cast. To his right he saw the floating wisps of magical energy coalescing into the hands of a Dark Elf. He turned to face the caster and started to bow in a formal greeting.  He had barely begun to bend at his waist when a bolt of fire shot out from the hands of the dark elf and struck him squarely in his chest. The heat from the magical fire seared his flesh and he cried out in pain as his body was enveloped with hot licks of flame.  He dropped his torch and fell to his knees, his hands gripping his thighs tightly as his body shook with pain. The pain remained after the brief flash of fire, but a moment later he was able to open his eyes.  He looked down at his hands and noticed they were reddened but still functional.  The hair along his arms was singed and shriveled, and he found himself reaching his face to feel if his eyebrows were still there.  The pain was subsiding as he confirmed the presence of his eyebrows and moustache.  His tunic was blackened and burned where the bolt of fire had struck him.<br>
<br>
&quot;You are weak, Dog!&quot; a voice said above him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Shall I burn him again and end his intrusion once and for all?&quot; said another.<br>
<br>
&quot;Let us see what he has to say on his own behalf,&quot; said the first voice.<br>
<br>
Raff felt a boot on his shoulder and looked up from his chest where he was examining his burned tunic.<br>
<br>
&quot;What are you here for, human worm?&quot; asked the owner of the second voice.  He was a shorter Dark Elf wearing a reddish gray robe.  His long white hair was a stark contrast to his blood red eyes and dark blue skin.  &quot;I asked you a question, human. If you should wish to live more than a moment from now, I would suggest you answer immediately.&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff swallowed and struggled to find his voice. He was nearly paralyzed with fear and knew the tiniest mistake now would cost him his life.  He managed to speak slowly, his voice remarkably even considering his hands were shaking against his thighs.  &quot;I seek entrance to your guild. I wish to learn the ways of the Teir'Dal, and learn the skills of a magician.&quot;<br>
<br>
The second Dark Elf pushed against Raff with his boot, causing him to topple from his knees.  &quot;Master T'Rald, we do not need any more initiates, especially one as useless this one.  May I destroy him?&quot;<br>
<br>
Master T'Rald looked down at Raff as he returned to a kneeling position.  &quot;Get up.&quot; He said simply.<br>
<br>
Raff moved to his feet as calmly as he could, trying to appear under control.  He recalled that the Teir’Dal despised weakness and forced himself to return the Dark Elf's gaze.  Master T'Rald looked older, even for a Dark Elf.  His black eyes were set deep into his head and topped with bushy white eyebrows.  His short hair was white and stood out sharply next to his dark blue skin.  He wore a full-length blood red robe with many yellow markings along the collar and cuffs.<br>
<br>
&quot;So human,&quot; he spoke quietly and looked unblinkingly at Raff, &quot;What makes you think we would want to train you?&quot;<br>
<br>
Show no weakness! Raff thought.  Just answer his question. Although he was shaking inside, Raff forced his voice to speak clearly.  &quot;My own people, of Freeport, have deemed me unworthy of their school.&quot;<br>
<br>
The second Dark Elf scowled. &quot;And you feel we would find you worthy where mere humans have not?&quot;  He stepped forward and slapped Raff across his face.  &quot;Now dog, I shall take pleasure in causing you great pain before I kill you.  And when I am done with you, I shall find your woman and see if she's worth my time.&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff grimaced and gritted his teeth.  His hands closed into fists and suddenly his fear was gone, replaced by a cold anger.  He turned to look at the younger Dark Elf, a look of deathly seriousness in his eyes.  &quot;You will regret that,&quot; he said quietly, his voice strained with anger.<br>
<br>
&quot;Enough Kezlat.  There is fire in this one.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Kezlat opened his mouth to reply, hesitated, and then moved back from Raff to stand beside the other Elf.<br>
<br>
&quot;What is your name, Human?&quot; asked Master T'Rald.<br>
<br>
Raff's willed his hands to unclench and his arms to relax.  &quot;Raff, Master.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That is a simple name, Human.  We do not just let anyone into our guild; you must prove yourself to be worthy of our teaching first.  Do you know of our Father, Innoruuk?&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff nodded.  &quot;Yes, I do know of Innoruuk.  He is the god of Hate, and the father of your people&quot;.<br>
<br>
Kezlat narrowed his eyes.  &quot;And what could you possibly know of Hate, dog?  You are a mere human.  You are not worthy of the father's strength.&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff sneered and turned to face Kezlat. &quot;I know I hate you,&quot; he said coldly.<br>
<br>
Kezlat watched Raff carefully, noticing the menacing look in the human's eyes.  He turned to look at T'Rald.  &quot;Master,&quot; he sneered, &quot;I ask for the chance to test this one.&quot;  He turned back to Raff, his own sneer spreading across his face. &quot;I wish to prove him unworthy to serve the Father.&quot;<br>
<br>
T'Rald nodded at his student. &quot;Very well, Kezlat, you shall get the chance.&quot;  He turned to Raff. &quot;In order to be accepted into our guild you must pass a test of worth.  Every initiate must pass this test, and it is quite simple, really, but few actually pass it.  All you must do is kill one of us in combat.  Those who volunteer to battle prospective initiates are most often new to our guild, but there is no restriction.  Any one of us can challenge one requiring initiation, but most often it is not worth the time for our advanced students.  Kezlat here is much more powerful than most initiates, and has already learned the basics of elemental summoning, but since has requested to be the one to test your worthiness, he shall be the one to do so.  Most initiates are tested by those students who have not yet learned the art of elemental summoning.  This shall be an interesting test indeed.  We shall soon know of your strength, human.&quot;<br>
<br>
T'Rald turned and strode away, his robe fluttering about him.  &quot;Come this way. We shall end this now.&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff followed after T'Rald quickly. Kezlat scowled at him as he walked past but then fell in behind him.  As they walked along they passed a number of students who questioned the presence of an unknown human in their guildhalls. The students rapidly exchanged whispers as they passed, often falling in behind the three.  By the time they reached the open area they were being followed by over a dozen young students, two of which were human.<br>
<br>
Raff looked around in the large cavern they'd entered.  He assumed he was standing in the space where he would soon be battling Kezlat. It was a large flat area surrounded by smooth stone walls rising over thirty feet above the battleground.  Above the walls, overlooking the battle area were rows of stone platforms, much like benches, where the students sat in order to get a good view of the upcoming fight.  Raff estimated this amphitheatre could easily hold 300 people.  The entire area was lit with a diffuse light provided by hundreds of glowing symbols similar to the one Raff had seen when he first entered Neriak.  When he completed his visual survey of the arena he noticed Master T'Rald had taken his seat in a dark polished stone chair raised about ten feet above the field.  Large stone steps, inlaid with the same strange glowing symbols he had noticed earlier, alternating between red and blue, lead up to the chair.  The chair, or throne as Raff considered it, was itself lined with blood red and deep dark purple glowing lines.  The lights helped give the entire area a surreal look, and Raff felt as if he was in a dream, regardless of the great peril his life was currently in.  He noticed there were four blood-red squares set into the stone floor, glowing dimly, one along each of the four sides of the area.  The Dark Elves seemed to have a fascination with the color of blood.  Raff considered that it might make clean up easier after a challenge.<br>
<br>
More students had filed in, and now the seating area held over 30 spectators, most of them talking quietly amongst themselves, no doubt speculating upon how quickly Raff would be destroyed by the more powerful Kezlat.  T'Rald cleared his throat and a blanket of silence fell upon the assemblage.  The Dark Elf master leaned forward in his chair, steepled his fingers as if in casual discussion, and then began to speak with a clear resonant voice.<br>
<br>
&quot;We are here this day to witness the test of worthiness of the human Raff.  He has requested that we admit him into our guild and train him in the ways of the magician.  Although Raff has no magical training whatsoever, Kezlat, a magician of the first rank of the second circle, has requested that he be the one to test the depth of Raff's strength.  In accordance with our customs, any other may test Raff if they can best Kezlat in combat first. Is there anyone who wishes to challenge Kezlat for the task of testing this human?&quot;<br>
<br>
T'Rald slowly scanned the crowd and waited patiently before speaking again.  Raff could feel a droplet of sweat roll down his forehead as he stood rigidly.  He was rapidly considering his alternatives, and there seemed to be few.  Escape was completely impossible, even if he would have considered it, and he would not; his path was laid out before him, and behind him there was nothing.  Slowly he clenched and unclenched his hands, allowing his right to fall closed on the handle of the knife he kept in his belt.  Gripping the handle tightly, drew the long knife out of it's scabbard slightly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Since there are no requests to challenge Kezlat,&quot; continued T'Rald &quot;I shall now allow him to prove the worthiness of this human.&quot;  He turned his head and spoke directly to Raff.  &quot;Now, human, you must know the rules under which this challenge will take place.  You will take your place opposite Kezlat, on one of the red squares.  Once Kezlat has reached his square, he will begin summoning an elemental.  It is his duty to destroy you, and it is your duty to destroy him.  His elemental will make things difficult for you, but, if you are strong enough, that will not matter.&quot;<br>
<br>
He turned his dark eyes upward and looked out across the arena to the crowd.  &quot;You may begin now.&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff watched as Kezlat bowed deeply before T'Rald and then he copied the Dark Elf, bowing deeply toward the throne.  As he did he removed the blade at his side fully from its scabbard.  His heart was racing in his chest, pounding insistently.  He stood stiffly and turned to see Kezlat's back as the Dark Elf walked toward the red square at the far end of the arena.  Raff's mind was whirling.  Once Kezlat reached his starting square, he would begin summoning an elemental and once the elemental appeared, Raff's death was assured.  Raff knew no magic whatsoever - no summoning, no protection, and no attack spells.  He glanced at the red square Kezlat was walking to, and then to its twin across the arena.  The distance was nearly 100 feet.  He knew if he tried to close that distance he would die before he was halfway to his enemy.  He knew at that instant, there was only one course of action open to him.  <br>
<br>
He turned toward Kezlat who was over twenty feet from him now and sprinted toward him.  He could feel the eyes of every person on him and Kezlat as he closed the distance between them.  Kezlat heard the scrape of Raff's boots on the stone floor, stopped and turned around to see what had caused the noise.  He had barely turned fully around when Raff plunged his knife deeply into his chest.  He clutched feebly at the knife, his eyes wide in shock, but Raff pulled the knife out as soon as it entered the Elf and brought it down again, harder, burying it to the hilt.  Raff's face was contorted in a sinister snarl as he viciously drove the knife again and again into the Dark Elf's chest.  He stabbed continuously until the Kezlat flopped to the ground, lifeless.  Raff looked at the dead Elf at his feet, and then at the blood slicked knife in his hand.  He was shaking with rage as he sheathed the knife, distantly aware of the blood spatters on his robe. He turned and walked back to the large black throne and bowed stiffly before T’Rald.  The arena had become utterly silent.<br>
<br>
&quot;I've done as you requested, Master.  I have defeated the challenger.  May I be granted admission to the guild?&quot;  He looked directly into T'Rald's face.<br>
<br>
T’Rald returned Raff’s gaze, his face unreadable. &quot;You have made a mockery of our custom human. You have killed a young magician by attacking when he was unprepared.  For this you request to be granted admission?&quot;  T’Rald’s voice was perfectly calm, belying no emotion whatsoever.<br>
<br>
Raff ‘s eyes burned with intensity. &quot;You asked me what I knew of Hate, Master, and I have this answer for you.”  He paused and looked around him at the stunned students, then slowly brought his gaze back to T’Rald.  “I hate losing.”<br>
<br>
T'Rald stared down at Raff for a long while, his face impassive.  Slowly a smile spread across his dark blue face, and finally he laughed.  &quot;Perhaps there is something to you after all human.   Perhaps you will have what it takes to be a magician of Neriak.  You have passed only one trial, Initiate Raff.  There will be many more, and they will be much more difficult.  May Innoruuk lend strength to your hate.&quot;<br>
<br>
With this he stood and walked gracefully down the steps, strode out of the arena, and disappeared. Minutes later the audience was gone as well, and Raff was the only person standing in the eerie blue and red glow.  <br>
<br>
A devastating feeling of utter aloneness washed over him and he fell to his knees and wept.<br>
<br>
