<br>
&quot;Do, you have a question concerning the power of Hate Chaydar?&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff sagged in his chair and groaned to himself.  If there was one thing he'd learned over the last two months in Neriak, it was to never, ever, get involved in a conversation with anyone about Innoruuk, the god of Hate.  The dark elves loved to pontificate endlessly on the wisdom of a life based on hate, and master Y'Ran was a priest of Innoruuk, and one of the most adamant teachers in Neriak.<br>
<br>
&quot;Please forgive my ignorance, master Y'Ran, but I only wish to learn more about the Father, and I don't have the benefit of growing up in the Teir'Dal society,” Chaydar said quietly, his eyes never straying to master Y'Ran's face.<br>
<br>
&quot;The error would be if you refused to learn about Our Father, and thus remained ignorant.  Ask.&quot;<br>
<br>
Chaydar cleared his throat nervously. &quot;Aren't some people, such as the Fier’Dal or the Koada'Dal, motivated by kindness?&quot; Chaydar paused while Master Y'Ran pursed his lips and stopped pacing.  &quot;I'm not suggesting their way is better, and in fact, I'd say they're foolish for allowing such silly notions to cloud their thoughts, but...&quot; Chaydar was speaking rapidly now, his words bumbling amongst themselves as he spoke.  &quot;I mean...&quot;<br>
<br>
Master Y'Ran raised his hand calmly and Chaydar fell silent.<br>
<br>
&quot;This is a typical view of humans, caused by a gross misunderstanding not only of Innoruuk's teachings, but also your own motivations.&quot; He paused, his hand remaining up, but with only one finger raised.  &quot;The Fier’Dal and Koada'Dal might think they are motivated by kindness, but in fact, they are not.&quot; Master Y'Ran smiled slightly. &quot;Take, for example, food.&quot; He turned his red eyes on Chaydar. &quot;Why do you eat Chaydar?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well... I suppose... because I'm hungry?  And eating makes me feel good?&quot; Chaydar answered, unsure of himself. &quot;Food tastes good?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No.&quot; Y'Ran's voice resonated clearly in the room. &quot;This is a typical answer from one who lacks knowledge.&quot;<br>
<br>
Chaydar lowered his head and said weakly, “Forgive me Master, I wish to learn.&quot;<br>
<br>
Master Y'Ran returned to his slow pacing, waving his hand at Chaydar dismissively.  &quot;It is not important that you do not know, but instead that you will know.&quot; He clasped his hands behind his back again and continued. &quot;You must approach this in terms of Hate Chaydar.  You must always think as Innoruuk instructs us.  You do not eat because it makes you feel good, but instead because you hate being hungry.  If you ate because eating made you feel good, then you would never stop eating.  Instead, you eat until your discomfort - your hunger, and your hatred of that hunger - is gone.  You are motivated by your hatred, not your pleasure.&quot;<br>
<br>
Y'Ran paused and turned his head slightly upward, a thoughtful expression on his face.  &quot;Initiate Raff, what are the prime emotional motivators?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Pain, suffering, and misery, Master Y'Ran.  And our hatred of them.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Very good Raff.  And why are we motivated to drink?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;We hate the sensation of thirst,&quot; Raff answered crisply.<br>
<br>
&quot;And why do we try to increase our power and influence?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;We merely hate the feelings of helplessness and weakness.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What of sex and love, initiate Raff?&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff fought a sickening feeling in his stomach.  &quot;It is the hatred we feel for irritation in the loins that drives us to copulate and love is an emotion inspired by self-hatred, the most powerful distillation of hate.  To love someone is to hate yourself enough to subjugate your mind to the will of another.&quot;  Raff spoke in a slow monotone as if he had recited the same sentence a thousand times.<br>
<br>
Master Y'Ran allowed a small smile to creep into his features.  &quot;Excellent Raff, as always.  You continue to grow in your knowledge and understanding.  Had you been born a Teir'Dal, you might have been able to be truly great.&quot;  He paused a moment to allow the compliment time to sink into the other students.<br>
<br>
&quot;You should all pattern yourselves after Raff, for he excels in his training.  In fact, right now you should be feeling a burning sting of hatred for him because he makes all of you appear weaker and less worthy.  Raff deserves your hatred!”  Master Y’Ran grinned at Raff.  “Raff, your excellence drives your fellow students to improve themselves.  You are a child of Innoruuk now.”<br>
<br>
He turned his gaze from Raff and looked among the other students.  “Now, for motivation and reinforcement of what you have learned, you should all go and destroy someone weaker than yourselves.  It is the natural order of life and Hate that the weaker will be destroyed by the stronger.  Only the strong deserve to continue in Innoruuk’s world.”<br>
<br>
“I want you to all go into Nektulos and slay some of the disgusting halflings that often camp at the edge of our woods.  Today, only Raff shall be allowed to deliver the killing blow because he is the most worthy among you.  The rest of you may only render your enemies unconscious and offer them to Raff.”<br>
<br>
He turned to Raff again.  “Raff, I want you to develop your keen sense of hatred and rightness further, so you will only kill with a blade this day.  You may use magic to subjugate your foes, but I want you to experience the feelings of complete control and power over another being.  When the other students have rendered the halflings unconscious, they will tie them up and deliver them to you.  You will awaken them by whatever means necessary and then sacrifice them to Innoruuk.  You will make them beg for release before you kill them so that you and your fellow students can see the futility of pleading and how it arises from weakness and inferiority.”<br>
<br>
Raff sat still, his face emotionless.  His mind was screaming at him, urging him to run from the room, to leave Neriak and never return.  For the thousandth time since he began studying amongst the Dark elves he felt nauseous and feared he would vomit.  He swallowed slowly and clenched his fists tightly.  Somewhere in the distant corners of his mind, he knew he was slowly losing a battle for his sanity.<br>
<br>
“I will be nearby to witness the development of your skills.” Y’Ran unsheathed a long silver knife from a black scabbard on his belt and offered it to Raff. “Today you will use my own knife, Raff”  <br>
<br>
Raff took the knife obediently, and spoke quietly.  “I will use it for Innoruuk’s work Master.”<br>
<br>
Y’Ran spoke to the group.  Go forth and spread hatred, students of Innoruuk&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes Master&quot; the group of students stood and responded in unison.  &quot;We go to do the Father's work&quot;<br>
<br>
The students left the room orderly, but quickly.  There were halflings to kill and torture. <br>
