<br>
&quot;I secured it in the guild library last night before I retired.&quot;  Konkir sat in a chair before Dooly, his hands fidgeting at his sides, betraying his nervousness.<br>
<br>
Dooly rolled his eyes and sighed, pushing his tiny body back from the desk.  &quot;Why wasn't the library secured?  Why did you allow such a precious scroll to go missing?&quot;<br>
<br>
Konkir glared at the gnome and pointed a slender finger at him.  &quot;I most certainly did make sure the library was secured, and don't you dare suggest it is my fault the scroll is lost!&quot; His voice was cracking.<br>
<br>
&quot;This isn't the first time you've blundered Konkir!  I remember a certain supply of malachite that went missing the day after...&quot;<br>
<br>
Konkir leapt to his feet.  &quot;You know that wasn’t my fault!&quot;  His thin frame was shaking with rage as he squeaked his indignation.<br>
<br>
Dooly stood up and returned the glare across the desk, tapping his finger on the desk for emphasis.  &quot;I wasn't the last one to use it, and I wasn't the one who left the library unattended, so I figure that...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Enough!&quot;  Tara declared.  She had been sitting quietly in the other chair in the room listening to the two mages argue with each other since Konkir entered the room to inform Dooly of the missing scroll.  &quot;We have a problem, and we need a solution.  We do not need the two of you fighting like children.&quot;<br>
<br>
Konkir breathed deeply, trying to calm himself.  Dooly scowled at Tara.<br>
<br>
 &quot;Sit down. Both of you,&quot; Tara repeated.<br>
<br>
&quot;We need more than a solution. We need to make sure this doesn't start again so we should ...&quot; Dooly started.<br>
<br>
&quot;I said SIT DOWN!&quot; Tara roared.  Tara Necklene wasn’t about to let Dooly or anyone else ignore her commands.<br>
<br>
Dooly opened his mouth and closed it wordlessly.  His face was now bright red.  Tara narrowed her eyes and returned Dooly's stare.  After a moment he shrugged and sat down slowly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Now,&quot; Tara began, &quot;which scroll are we talking about?  Is it an important one?&quot;<br>
<br>
Konkir looked over at Dooly and then turned to Tara. &quot;It's the new scroll our expedition to Velious found.  As far as we can tell, it's a new summoning spell.   Something we've never seen before.&quot;  He shrugged.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's huge,” added Dooly, pursing his lips at Konkir for emphasis.  &quot;And now it's gone.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tara glanced at Dooly, a warning in her brown eyes, and the gnome was silent.  &quot;So. It's important then.&quot;  Dooly nodded, resisting the urge to speak again.  &quot;Do we have a copy of the spell?&quot;  Tara asked, turning to Konkir.<br>
<br>
Konkir sighed and worked his hands nervously in his lap.  &quot;No.  We had just started deciphering it. It was written in Elder Dragon, and was extremely difficult to work on.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tara steepled her fingers, placed her index fingers to her lips and thought for a moment.  &quot;Is there anyone who might know about this spell?  Somebody who would know we have it in our possession?&quot;<br>
<br>
Konkir and Dooly looked at each other reflexively then dropped their eyes.  Tara watched them and raised an eyebrow.  &quot;Well?&quot; he asked.<br>
<br>
Konkir looked up, his voice low. &quot;We have reason to believe the Dark Summoners in Neriak have taken this half.”<br>
<br>
Tara narrowed her eyes in confusion.  &quot;I'm sorry?  This half?  What does that mean?&quot;<br>
<br>
It was Dooly's turn to sigh.  &quot;The original spell was torn in two, supposedly in order to protect it's secret.  We’ve been working on the first half.  We believe the Teir'Dal managed to find out about the spell and steal it, and now that they have the first half, they’ll be after the second half.”<br>
 <br>
Tara cocked her head sideways slightly, a finger rubbing her lower lip lightly.  “And what gives you reason to suspect the Teir’Dal?<br>
<br>
“We were effectively in a race to reach the scroll in the first place.  When we arrived in Velious there was a Teir’Dal party already there, preparing for their exploration.  One of our party overheard the Dark Elves discussing a few of the possible locations for the scroll… the same locations we had discovered in our research,” Konkir explained.<br>
<br>
Dooly rubbed his bald temple and sighed.  “But we beat them to it!  And now the bastards managed to steal it from our own library.”  He sighed again and leaned back in his chair.  “And now… we only have half a spell.”<br>
<br>
Tara looked at Dooly and then Konkir.  “Where is the other half?”  She asked slowly.<br>
<br>
“Oh don’t worry about that, we’ve hidden it very carefully, and it’s under secure lock.”  Konkir replied.<br>
<br>
“How do you know it’s secure if the other half was stolen so easily?” Tara asked.<br>
<br>
“The first half was locked in the study area of the library because it was being researched.  We were only working on the first half, so the second half was, and is, safely stored in our vaults.  They’re too heavily protected for anyone to attempt a theft.  It would be suicide.” Konkir said confidently.<br>
<br>
“Then why the hell didn’t you store the first half in the vaults as well?”  Dooly accused, his eyes flashing at Konkir.<br>
<br>
“Dooly, be silent.  Your infantile accusations aren’t helping this situation.  You know very well material being researched isn’t placed in the vaults because it takes hours to safely remove the  protection spells.”  Tara’s look silenced any response the gnome considered. Instead he allowed a sour look to spread across his face as he folded his arms across his chest.<br>
<br>
Tara was silent while she considered the problem facing them.  “So, I take it the second half of the spell is useless without the first half?”  Konkir nodded.  “How far did you get on researching the spell Konkir?”<br>
<br>
“Not far enough to complete the spell with just the second half, if that’s what you’re thinking,” Konkir said.<br>
<br>
“So, we need the first half back.  Perhaps we can use the second half as a bargaining chip, and make a trade with the Dark Summoners then.”<br>
<br>
Konkir nodded.  “That might work.  They might go for that.”<br>
<br>
“That would mean the Teir’Dal would get a complete copy of the spell then”  Dooly complained.<br>
<br>
“Do you have a better solution Mr. Jonkers?”  Tara asked.  Dooly stared at Tara for a few moments and then sighed heavily.<br>
<br>
“As I thought.  So.  What are our options?”  Tara looked at Konkir.<br>
<br>
Konkir looked at his feet a moment and said quietly.  “Well, I suppose we could make a copy of the spell for them, but change a small piece to confuse them.  They would find out eventually, and solve the problem, but we might get a head start that way.”<br>
<br>
“A good suggestion.  Could you make a copy authentic looking enough to fool them?”  Tara asked.<br>
<br>
“I think so… it might take a while, but I think I could.”<br>
<br>
“But how do we contact the Dark Elves?  We haven’t had any contact with them for over a decade.  They’d kill any of us who attempted to contact them.  They’ve all but sworn to destroy anyone from the Academy.  And it’s almost impossible to hire a rogue these days to enter Neriak, and even if we could find one brave enough and skilled enough, they’d probably screw us over for more money.  You can’t trust anyone who associates with them.”  Dooly’s voice became more agitated as he talked.<br>
<br>
“I can think…” Konkir started.<br>
<br>
“True Dooly.  But we might have to resort to an extreme measure in this extreme circumstance” Tara noted.<br>
<br>
“I can think…” Konkir tried again.<br>
<br>
“Any Dark Elf would screw us.  Period!”  Dooly repeated.<br>
<br>
“I can think of someone who might be able to help us,” Konkir said quietly.<br>
<br>
“Yes Konkir?” Tara invited.<br>
<br>
“There’s someone who is attending the Dark Summoners right now, and I think he’d like to get out, and finish his training here at the Academy.  He’s not a Dark Elf, and I’ve heard he absolutely hates it in Neriak,” Konkir offered.<br>
<br>
Dooly’s eyes opened wide and his face flushed red.  “No!  Absolutely NOT!”  He waved his had and held it up toward Konkir.  “I will NOT have that bastard working for us – he’s nothing but a …<br>
<br>
“Fortunately, Dooly, it’s not your decision to make,” Tara interrupted.  <br>
<br>
Dooly scowled at Tara, his cheeks crimson.  “This is a terrible idea Necklene.  Mark my words,”  he was tapping on his desk again with his tiny index finger, emphasizing each word.  “We will regret this decision.”<br>
<br>
“Then it will be MY decision we regret,” Tara said, a finality in her voice that made Dooly realize the discussion was over.  She turned to look at Konkir.  “Send a message to Raff informing him that we wish to speak with him, and that it’s extremely important.”<br>
<br>
Dooly muttered under his breath and folded his arms again.<br>
<br>
“I will send the message immediately Tara,” Konkir said as he rose from his chair.<br>
<br>
“Good.  Inform me as soon as you receive word from him in any fashion.”  Tara rose from her chair.  “We are done here then.”<br>
<br>
Konkir followed Tara out and closed the door quietly behind them.  Dooly leaned back in his chair, turned his face to the ceiling, closed his eyes, and shook his head silently.<br>
