<br>
Raff stood at the gates of Freeport, a crumpled note in his hand.  He stared into the distance at nothing in particular while he considered the possibilities his future might entail. What in hell do they want from me? He thought.  He looked down at the parchment in his hand, slowly opened it and for the twentieth time, read it.<br>
<br>
To Raff, onetime resident of Freeport, widow of Glorias:<br>
<br>
The Academy of Arcane Science requests your presence as soon as possible to discuss an urgent task.<br>
<br>
Although we have had tense relations in the past, the Academy wishes to start anew.<br>
<br>
We look forward to seeing you again.<br>
<br>
Raff crumpled the note in his fist and breathed deeply.  Whatever this is about, they must want it pretty damn badly to need someone who they couldn't associate with two years ago. On his way from Neriak to Freeport he had tried to think of what the Academy could want from him, a mere apprentice magician, but he couldn't think of anything he could do that could possibly interest them. Well, he thought, no time like the present, I suppose.<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
As Raff entered the city, walking under the stone archway above the entrance to Freeport, a Dark Elf appeared suddenly just outside the gates directly in front of a city guard.  The guard’s head snapped toward the Dark Elf and he scowled.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Who are you, and what business do you have in Freeport Teir'Dal?&quot; The guard spoke in a low gravely voice.<br>
<br>
The Dark Elf watched Raff disappear down a side street, his eyes never straying from him.<br>
<br>
&quot;My name is Kezlat Human, and my business is none of your concern,&quot; he said while beginning to cast a spell. Three seconds later, he vanished.<br>
<br>
The last thing the guard saw of Kezlat was the beginnings of a broad smile spreading across his dark blue features.<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
Raff arrived at the Academy of Arcane Science after a short walk.  Two members greeted him as he walked through the large stone archway that marked the entrance.  Beyond the archway was a narrow street ending in a teleportation platform.  Raff stepped on the platform and immediately found himself inside the Academy facing two female members wearing purple robes.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hello Raff,&quot; the first woman spoke brightly &quot;It's so nice to see you again.&quot;<br>
<br>
 &quot;I doubt it,” he said firmly.<br>
<br>
The woman blinked in confusion.  &quot;I'm sorry...?&quot; she said, more as a question than a statement of sorrow.<br>
<br>
Raff looked around casually, noticing some younger members having a discussion a few feet away.  &quot;I know as well as anyone I'm not wanted here, so don't insult me with your pretentious blathering.&quot;<br>
<br>
The woman gaped at Raff, her mouth open in surprise. &quot;Well... I didn't mean to ... uh... blather... uh, I was just...”<br>
<br>
&quot;I see you've picked up some Teir'Dal habits Raff.  I hope you still have some feelings for your own race, my friend,” said a woman stepping forward from a stairway leading upward.  She walked forward with a confidence long nurtured in a position of authority. She bowed before Raff.<br>
<br>
&quot;If the habits you refer to are my ability to tell when someone's wasting my time with lies and pomp and my refusal to waste time, then you'd be correct. They're habits most humans would do well to learn.&quot;<br>
<br>
When the woman smiled at Raff he was instantly aware of her beauty. Her smile seemed to touch her brown eyes and Raff found he liked her.  &quot;I couldn't agree more Raff,&quot; she said lightly.  &quot;We could use a lot more candor in this place.  My name is Tara Necklene, and I'm one of the senior instructors here.&quot;  She bowed again.<br>
<br>
Raff found himself fighting the urge to bow.  &quot;What do you want with me?&quot; he asked coldly.<br>
<br>
Tara smiled again and glanced around the room.  &quot;Let's go up to my office.  I think we'll have more privacy there.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tara turned around and went up the stairs with Raff following her as she walked three flights up into the Academy. When she finally stopped on the third floor she paused and turned to Raff.  &quot;There are two more people I'd like you to meet.  Well, that's not entirely true; I believe you've met one of them before.&quot;  She walked down a short corridor and opened a door at the end, then motioned for Raff to enter. &quot;After you,&quot; she said.<br>
<br>
Raff entered the small room and glanced at the large wooden desk that dominated the office.  In front of the desk were three chairs, two of which were occupied. He paused momentarily as his eyes locked onto the gnome sitting in the chair furthest from the door.  He had no trouble remembering the gnome's name:  Dooly Jonkers.  &quot;I see the Academy still maintains a staff of arrogant bastards,&quot; he said as he stared at Dooly, his face impassive.  Dooly started to respond, but stopped, apparently thinking it wasn't the best time for comment.<br>
<br>
&quot;Please Raff, have a seat.&quot; Tara motioned Raff forward, casually trying to break the tension.  As Raff moved toward the nearest chair she walked around the large desk and sat down behind it.  Raff went behind the closest chair but made no move to sit down.<br>
<br>
&quot;Please Raff, sit down,&quot; Tara repeated.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'd rather stand, thank you,” he said formally.<br>
<br>
&quot;As you wish.&quot; She replied and smiled.  &quot;Allow me to introduce Konkir, our chief researcher here at the Academy.&quot;  Tara indicated Konkir with a wave of her hand and the thin man stood and bowed. Raff merely nodded.<br>
<br>
&quot;I believe you know Dooly here,&quot; she said nodding at Dooly.  &quot;Dooly is in charge of admissions and student relations.&quot;  Dooly glanced at Raff and licked his tiny lips, but didn't acknowledge him in any way.<br>
<br>
Raff looked at Tara and said, &quot;Yes, I've had the great displeasure of meeting him before.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tara continued, unshaken by Raff's blunt comment.  &quot;Good.  We can begin then.  Now, to answer your question. Why are you here? The answer is both simple and complex, but since you seem like a man who prefers straightforward answers, I'll be brief.  Essentially we need you to act as a go-between for a small trade we need to do with the Dark Summoners of Neriak.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I see.  And what is the item to be traded?&quot; Raff's voice was calm and quiet.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's a scroll, Raff.&quot;  Konkir's voice was high pitched, a perfect match to his frail build.  &quot;We have half of it, and the Dark Summoners stole the other half from our library.  We found the spell in two pieces in Velious a while back.&quot;  Konkir was speaking rapidly, his interest in the spell obvious.  &quot;It's quite and interesting spell, actually, and when we get both pieces back, it'll will be a great spell!  In fact...”<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you Konkir, that's all we need right now,&quot; Tara interrupted. She held her hands out in front of her, palms toward each other. &quot;So, all we need you to do is take a copy of our spell and trade it for a copy of the other half.  That way both guilds will have a copy of the spell.&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff looked from Konkir to Tara. &quot;Why me?&quot; he asked quietly. Dooly muttered something under his breath.<br>
<br>
Tara shot a warning glance at Dooly and then turned back to Raff. &quot;To be honest Raff, you're the only one we could think of that might have sympathies for both the Teir'Dal and the Humans. Would you be willing to do this for us?&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff stood silently for a while, looking at the others in the room. He sighed and slowly sat down in the chair Tara had offered before.  He rested his hands on the arms of the chair and looked up at the ceiling.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll do this for you on three conditions,&quot; he began.<br>
<br>
&quot;What three conditions?&quot;  Dooly spoke for the first time, his words dripping with condescension. &quot;Two bottles of wine and a mug of ale?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No... No, not that Dooly&quot; Raff stood up slowly and moved to Dooly's chair.  As he did, Dooly stood in response, his arms folding across his chest.  When Raff was directly before him Dooly's head came up to Raff's waist.<br>
<br>
&quot;What then Raff? Maybe two bottles of wine and a bar slut?” Dooly shrugged and chuckled. “Of course, you might be spoiled by now. I hear Neriak prostitutes excel in their craft.&quot;  Dooly laughed.<br>
<br>
Raff smiled at Dooly and then struck him hard across the face with a solid fist, his weight fully behind the blow, sending the tiny gnome flying into the chair and toppling both over.  Konkir and Tara jumped from their seats to intervene, but Raff calmly turned and moved back to his chair and sat down.<br>
<br>
Dooly scrambled to his feet, disentangling himself from the chair.  &quot;Why you stupid little bastard,&quot; he growled, his face bright red with anger.  &quot;What the hell was that for?&quot; He put his fingers to his lips and when he pulled them away they were bloody.<br>
<br>
&quot;That,&quot; Raff said calmly, &quot;Was condition number one.&quot;<br>
<br>
Dooly glared at Raff but the human ignored him.  Konkir looked to Dooly and then to Tara, who sat down quickly, fighting the smile that had just started to form on her face.  Konkir watched Dooly sit down and then did so himself, a stunned expression on his face.  The gnome took a handkerchief from inside his robes and wiped his mouth gingerly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Alright Raff, that's number one.  What are the other two conditions?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Second is that I get to learn the spell before I take it to Neriak.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Out of the question!&quot; Dooly said, his tiny fist thumping on the arm of his chair. He wiped his mouth again.<br>
<br>
Raff sat in his chair and spoke quietly.  &quot;That's what it's going to take for me to do this. If you want someone else, go ahead and get someone else, but if you want me to do it, I'm going to have access to the spell to learn it.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ridiculous!&quot; Dooly affirmed.  &quot;There's no way he deserves to have access to such a rare and powerful spell.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Raff, I mean no offense,&quot; Konkir started, &quot;but I don't think you'd be able to understand it.  You simply don't have the skills yet. You might one day, but not now, I'm afraid.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That would be my problem, wouldn't it?&quot;  Raff said.<br>
<br>
&quot;Dooly,&quot; Tara began, &quot;It's true. Raff probably won't be able to understand the spell anyway.  What harm would there be in allowing him to try learning it?&quot;<br>
<br>
Dooly turned his eyes away from Tara and folded his arms. &quot;Either way, it's a bad idea,” he said, half mumbling to himself.<br>
<br>
&quot;Konkir, what realistic chance does Raff have of understanding the spell?&quot; Tara asked.<br>
<br>
Konkir thought a moment. &quot;Virtually none.&quot; He said. &quot;If he did manage to learn the spell he'd be the most gifted magician I've ever heard of. I'm quite sure the Dark Elves don't teach much differently than we do, and even if they did, the spell would still be greatly beyond his capabilities. I'm sure he couldn't even muster the mana to power the spell.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tara nodded at Konkir and said, &quot;Very well then Raff, request granted. What is the third condition?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll need at least two full days undisturbed with the spell so I can work on learning it.&quot;  Raff said.<br>
<br>
&quot;That shouldn't be a problem.  Now, what is the third request?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I want to be paid 1000 platinum for my time.&quot;<br>
<br>
Dooly snorted but remained silent.  Tara looked at him questioningly.  He waved his hand dismissively.  &quot;I really don't care how much we pay him,&quot; he said.<br>
<br>
Tara looked at Konkir and he nodded.  &quot;Alright,&quot; she said, looking back at Raff. &quot;1000 platinum is fine. Do we have a deal now?&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff nodded and stood up. &quot;Yes. We have a deal.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tara stood and moved around her desk to offer her hand to Raff. They shook hands briefly and she said, &quot;You can come by tomorrow morning and start learning the spell. The following day you may come back and continue. On the third day you will leave in the morning with our copy of the spell. When you return from Neriak with the other half, we'll pay you the money. How does that sound Raff?&quot; She asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;That's fine,&quot; he said and turned to leave. He opened the door and turned back to her. &quot;I'll be here at dawn tomorrow,&quot; he said, and then he walked out of the room, closing the door behind him.<br>
<br>
Tara leaned against her desk, her hands gripping the edge.  &quot;Comments?&quot; she asked.  Konkir shook his head.  Dooly remained silent.  &quot;Alright then, make sure you two have the copy ready for the day after tomorrow.&quot;<br>
<br>
Konkir stood up and nodded. &quot;That won't be a problem Tara.  I'm almost finished a copy.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Good then. That's all for now.&quot;  She stood back up and walked around her desk to sit in her chair once again.  Konkir bowed and then left. Dooly stood and followed Konkir silently, closing the door behind him.<br>
<br>
If Dooly or Konkir had thought to look behind them as they walked back to their offices they might have noticed a slight movement of a few tapestries moments after they passed them.<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
Kezlat appeared from nothing a few feet from the entrance to the Academy of Arcane Science, chuckling quietly to himself.<br>
<br>
&quot;So, dear Raff. You've managed to stumble on a new spell! Your luck is truly amazing, but it won't do you any good whatsoever.&quot; Kezlat chuckled again to himself. <br>
<br>
An elderly man dressed in a collection of rags and shreds of leather walked up to him.  &quot;Could ya spare some coppers?&quot; he asked obsequiously.<br>
<br>
Kezlat's smile grew into a large grin. &quot;Certainly I can, Human,&quot; Kezlat said brightly as he opened his belt pouch and removed a few copper coins. &quot;Here you are,&quot; he said as he handed the man a handful of coins.<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you sir,&quot; the old man said, bowing deeply repeatedly. &quot;Much appreciated, it is.&quot;<br>
<br>
The old man turned to leave just as Kezlat spoke again &quot;Oh, my, I forgot. There is something you could do for me.&quot;<br>
<br>
The beggar turned back to Kezlat. &quot;Yes sir?&quot; he asked. &quot;What kin I do fer ya?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kezlat continued to grin as he placed his hand on the old man's shoulder. &quot;Oh, nothing really, something quite simple, in fact.&quot;<br>
<br>
The old man looked at Kezlat with one eye. His other appeared badly damaged, perhaps in a fight in the distant past, and was now virtually immobile. The Elf could smell stale sweat, urine and alcohol in the old man's clothes and he noticed he had few teeth left. Kezlat removed his long knife from his belt, looked deeply into the old man’s good eye and spoke softly, &quot;Just one little thing, old man.&quot; He pulled the man's face to his chest firmly, burying his grizzled face in his thick robes, and put his lips close to his ear. &quot;Die for me,” Kezlat whispered.  He pressed the knife against the old man’s side and drove it in to the hilt, twisting it once he had it embedded fully.  The old man convulsed and tried to remove himself from Kezlat's grasp, but the Dark Elf held him tightly to his chest, smothering his attempts to cry out. He twisted the knife viciously in the man's side and held him tightly until he stopped struggling.<br>
<br>
He released the old man and allowed his body to fall to the ground. He bent and wiped his knife on the man's dirty clothes then replaced it in his belt. &quot;For you, Father Innoruuk,&quot; he said quietly as walked away.<br>
