Kezlat sat quietly sipping a glass of wine in a secluded corner of the Blind Fish tavern. He was in a especially good mood tonight, even though he was out a few platinum he'd paid for the teleport to Nektulos forest.  Every once in a while, between sips, he chuckled out loud in spite of his efforts to remain silent.<br>
<br>
Another Dark Elf slipped into a chair across from him quietly, placing a mug of ale on the table. His long white hair and red eyes made him look remarkably similar to Kezlat, even though Kezlat looked much younger, lacking the maturity reflected in the other Elf's features.<br>
<br>
&quot;You wanted to speak to me?&quot; the second Elf asked gruffly.<br>
<br>
Kezlat smiled broadly. &quot;Yes, Zalar, I did. I am glad you came brother.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zalar frowned. &quot;Out with it Kezlat, I do not have time for Koada'Dal pleasantries.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Have you heard, dear brother, of a new spell acquired recently by the Dark Summoners? A spell originally from Velious, but most recently from the Academy of Arcane Science?&quot;  Kezlat spoke conspiratorially, his face still grinning.<br>
<br>
Zalar took a sip of ale, his face betraying no emotion. &quot;Perhaps. Why do you ask brother?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kezlat drew his finger along the rim of his wine glass slowly. &quot;Well, it just so happens I know somebody who will be carrying the second part of that particular spell from Freeport to Neriak.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zalar considered. &quot;And who is this person?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kezlat laughed darkly. &quot;My good friend Raff.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zalar raised an eyebrow.  Kezlat looked up from his wine glass, grinning, and nodded his head in response to his brother’s unspoken question.  The older Elf sucked at his lower lip and leaned back in his chair.<br>
<br>
&quot;I hear the Commons are dangerous this time of year... anything could happen to someone traveling through on their way to Neriak.&quot; Now it was Zalar's turn to smile.<br>
<br>
&quot;The person who learned this spell would gain great respect among the Dark Summoners,&quot; Kezlat added.<br>
<br>
&quot;And after they learned the spell, they could sell its secrets for a premium, I would suspect.&quot; Zalar took another drink of ale. &quot;When?&quot; he asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Two days from now. I will meet him in the commons and persuade him to donate the scroll to me.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Will you kill him?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No, that might cause complications.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Complications? How?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;As an official member of our guild, he has had his spirit bound in Neriak. If I killed him, he would most likely be resurrected in Neriak before I returned. Even though it would cost him a great deal of money, there are those loyal to him in the guild that would offer to pay. I do not need to remind you that there are many who believe he will become a powerful magician, and thus wish to keep him in their fold.&quot; Kezlat placed his hands on the table palms down. &quot;No, as much as I wish to destroy Raff, this is not the best time. It would be better if I just allowed him to return to Neriak on his own.&quot; He smiled at his brother again. &quot;That way you can learn the spell before he returns, and then we can present it to Master T'Rald.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zalar drank deeply from his mug and sat back thoughtfully, rubbing his temple absently. After a few moments he looked at Kezlat and nodded. &quot;Yes, I think, brother, that you will do the name of K'Rin proud with this plan.&quot; He reached forward for the mug, drained it in one swallow, and then stood up, pushing his chair behind him. &quot;I will secure a copy of the second half tonight and begin studying it. Notify me immediately when you return to Neriak with the other half.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kezlat watched as his brother left. He sipped slowly at his wine, savoring the wine's flavor and his own brilliance.<br>
