&quot;If you need anything, I'll be in the main room.&quot; Konkir said as he stood by the door to the private reading room.  <br>
<br>
Raff sat down at the large desk and laid out the scroll using two polished paper weights on each end to keep it flat. &quot;Thank you Konkir. I should be fine though.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Very well,&quot; Konkir said as he closed the door.<br>
<br>
Raff got up and moved to the door. He placed a large bar across it, effectively securing it from outside entry. The room was windowless, and thus protected from prying eyes. He went to the desk and pushed the large scroll to one side, retrieved a tightly folded scroll from inside his breaches, unfolded it and placed it beside the other scroll. He also put an inkpot and a sharpened quill beside the scrolls, and brought one of the magical light sources closer to the desk. When all was arranged properly he sat down and began the arduous task that would consume the next two days.<br>
<br>
Even a cursory look at the scroll told Raff t hat he didn't have a chance of understanding it. He recognized some words and symbols, but the scroll's deeper meanings were lost to him. That didn’t matter to him, however, because he’d never intended to learn the spell. He knew it was beyond him at this time, but he also knew that one day it would be well within his abilities. His plan was to have the scroll available to him when that day arrived.<br>
<br>
So, with the future in mind, he began the painstaking task of copying the scroll out word for word, symbol for symbol. It was extraordinarily difficult work because he didn't even recognize some of the symbols in the spell, so he had to copy them as perfectly as possible. He worked non-stop for the entire day and after ten hours he’d copied over half of the spell and the smaller scroll he'd been writing on was full on both sides.<br>
<br>
He rose and stretched slowly. His wrist ached painfully and he rubbed it lightly. He spread some drying sand on the scroll to prevent the ink form blotting, folded it carefully and then placed it back inside his breaches where it couldn’t be seen. After the scroll was safely hidden away he rolled up the original and placed it back in its case.<br>
<br>
He removed the brace from the door, and left the room, massaging his wrist absently. He called out for Konkir and was startled to see the slender human standing three feet away.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah, you are done?&quot; Konkir asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, for the day. I'll be back tomorrow.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Any luck?<br>
<br>
&quot;No, not really.” Raff sighed in feigned frustration. “I can understand some of it, but most is completely unintelligible to me.&quot;<br>
<br>
Konkir nodded his head. &quot;I expected as much Raff. Really, I don't think we would have let you in there if we thought you could really learn it.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yeah, I figured so. But you can't fault me for trying, can you? Raff laughed lightly.<br>
<br>
&quot;No, Raff. Perhaps you'll be a good librarian some day. You seem to have the patience for it.&quot; Konkir smiled kindly.<br>
<br>
Raff laughed again. &quot;A librarian? Somehow I can't see myself as a librarian, Konkir.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, you'd be surprised Raff. You never know.&quot;<br>
<br>
Raff nodded. &quot;No, I suppose you're right Konkir. I'd never have guessed I'd be studying to be a magician in Neriak either, so who knows?&quot; He shrugged. &quot;Well, goodnight Konkir. I'll see you tomorrow.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Goodnight Raff,&quot; Konkir said as he walked into the room where Raff had been working. He went to the case where the scroll was kept, opened it quickly, and removed the scroll so he could inspect it.<br>
<br>
He heard Raff's voice coming from across the library &quot;Don't worry Konkir, it's still there.&quot;<br>
<br>
Konkir smiled as he examined the scroll carefully. When he was positive it hadn't been tampered with in any way, he rolled it up and placed it back in its case. Once the scroll was secured he left the room and closed the door, making sure all the locks were in place.<br>
