<br>
Tara handed the small metallic cylinder to Raff. “Here’s a copy of the scroll Raff. We’ll pay you the one thousand platinum when you return with the other half.” Tara smiled at Raff, her expression comforting. “Are you set to go?” she asked.<br>
<br>
Raff accepted the scroll case and examined it while he spoke. “Yes Tara, I think I’m ready.” He turned the case over in his hand. It was shiny, perhaps made of steel, he thought, and he could see his warped reflection in it’s curved surface when he held it before him. The image was a grotesque-looking man with an enormous head and arms that disappeared into tiny sticks as they went further from his body.<br>
<br>
“Were you able to learn anything from the original?” Tara asked.<br>
<br>
Raff was staring intently at the scroll case. One end was completely sealed off, the metal rounded perfectly. The other end had a lid made of the same metal on it, but it was covered with some type of waxy substance.<br>
<br>
“Raff?”<br>
<br>
Raff looked up from the cylinder and blinked. “Sorry?” he asked.<br>
<br>
Tara laughed lightly. “I asked you if you learned anything from the original scroll.” She smiled again.<br>
<br>
“Oh,” Raff replied and looked down at the scroll case again. “No,” he said. “I didn’t really. It was too hard for me to make anything of it.” He ran his finger along the waxy ring on the scroll case. “What’s this?” he asked.<br>
<br>
“The seal? That’s a wax seal Raff. It’s so the Dark Summoners know the scroll hasn’t been tampered with.” She took the case from Raff and turned it halfway around until an impression in the wax could be seen. “You see?” She pointed at the impression. “That’s our guild insignia.”<br>
<br>
Raff nodded. “That makes sense.” He took the case back from her and placed it in his backpack carefully. “Is there anything else I need?” <br>
<br>
“No Raff. That’s all you need. There’s a letter inside explaining what we want in return for this scroll.”<br>
<br>
Raff pulled his backpack on and tightened the straps. “Well, I suppose I should get going then. I have a long trip ahead of me, and you want your scroll back as soon as possible.”<br>
<br>
Tara smiled again. “Good journey to you Raff. I hope we’ll see you again soon.”<br>
<br>
Raff simply nodded and then walked out of her office. Ten minutes later he was at the gates of Freeport, and on his way to Neriak.<br>
<br>
* * *<br>
<br>
Raff stopped to rest after a few hours on the road. He wasn’t particularly tired, but his curiosity was getting the best of him. He knelt down by the side of the road, placing his backpack in front of him, and retrieved a flask of water and a slice of fresh bread. As he chewed on the bread he pulled the scroll case from his pack and examined it again. His fingers traced along the waxy impression slowly and he chewed thoughtfully. What did they write to the Dark Summoners? He contemplated. Perhaps something like ‘please kill this messenger because he knows too much’? If there was one thing Raff had learned in his 39 years in Norrath, it was to never, ever trust anyone. He couldn’t trust the Summoners, and he certainly couldn’t trust the Academy. Sighing heavily, he allowed his fingernail to scrape the wax impression off the cylinder. The red wax peeled and flaked as he pressed along the rim. He put the last bit of bread in his mouth and, grabbing the cylinder with both hands, twisted the lid off. Reaching into the case, he pulled out a thick tube of paper and carefully rolled it open. As he did, another scroll slipped out and landed on the grass. The larger scroll was the spell itself, and the smaller one appeared to be the letter Tara had mentioned. Raff put the scroll case down on the larger scroll and opened the smaller one. He was almost afraid to read it, fearing what it might say.<br>
<br>
For the Dark Summoners<br>
<br>
On behalf of the Freeport Academy of Arcane Science, I wish to offer the Dark Summoners a trade. We are well aware that you have in your possession the first half of a previously unknown spell. This spell was taken from our private library a short time ago. We are well aware that it is now in your possession.<br>
<br>
Inside the scroll case you will find the second half of this scroll. We offer this to you with the understanding that you will offer us in return the first half. We further understand that you have no reason to return the first half of the scroll to us, so we have rendered this half of the spell useless. There are a few key parts missing. There is no doubt that you will, in time, decipher the scroll and determine the missing elements. However, if you were to return the first part of the scroll to us, we will supply the correct scroll in its entirety. If you should choose to keep both halves, you will undoubtedly be closer to complete understanding, but still considerably distant.<br>
<br>
I am sure, when you consider the alternatives, you will agree to return the scroll to us.<br>
<br>
Tara Necklene, on behalf of the Freeport Academy of Arcane Science<br>
<br>
Raff laughed lightly and shook his head. One day these people are going to drown in their own deceit and subterfuge he thought. He grabbed at another piece of bread and flask of water and lay down on the cool grass, the letter still in his hand. As he ate, he lay deep in thought, slowly tapping the letter against his leg. He popped the last bit of bread into his mouth and washed it down with some water. Getting up, he brushed some breadcrumbs from his tunic, and, folding the note up tightly, placed it in his backpack. He reached into his breaches, retrieved the scroll he’d carefully copied down, opened it up, and placed it beside the one he was supposed to offer as a trade and sat down again. The symbols meant no more to him today than they did two days ago, but he placed a finger on each scroll and carefully traced his way along the writings, comparing one to the other. It took him over half an hour before he found any discrepancy in the first scroll. He wasn’t able to discern what it meant, but he could tell there was a significant change – much more than just a few symbols.<br>
<br>
He was about to throw away the incorrect scroll when something made him stop. He couldn’t quite place the feeling, but something told him to keep the first scroll. He considered his options for a while, running his fingers through his moustache as he thought. Finally, he took the Academy’s scroll and placed it back in the scroll tube without the letter and then spent a few moments removing all traces of the wax seal from the shiny metal before he put the case back in his pack. He folded the letter up with the scroll he’d copied and returned it to his breaches. Standing up, he slung his backpack over his shoulder and looked down the road, into the distance. Looking at the sky, he figured there was another six hours of daylight from the position of the sun in the sky. He drained his flask and continued on his journey.<br>
<br>
* * *<br>
<br>
Raff watched the sun as it was fading on the horizon, bringing darkness with it. He had stopped a little over half an hour earlier to make camp by the side of the road. His little fire was burning down so he placed a few dry branches on top of it and watched the flames lick hungrily along the wood. The new branches cracked and spat in protest. As he emptied a flask of water into a small pot he heard a footstep nearby, the telltale snap of a twig. He dropped the pot, leapt to his feet and turned to face the noise, his hand falling on his dagger. The unmistakable shiver of magic fluttered through him and his feet were rooted to the ground where he stood. He overbalanced and fell to his hands and knees, his feet unmoving.<br>
<br>
“Well, well, well. If it isn’t my good friend Raff”<br>
<br>
Raff looked up to see a large irregularly shaped conglomeration of earth and rock floating inches from his face, flexing its stony arms. He struggled to stand up but the end of a staff pressed to his back pushed him back down.<br>
<br>
“Kezlat,” Raff said as he twisted around to see his attacker, trying to get to his feet again. “Didn’t I kill you once already?”<br>
<br>
A brown blur flashed before Raff’s eyes just before he felt the boot strike his head. He fell to the ground again, bright flashes of light exploding in his eyes. He felt blood flowing from his nose.<br>
<br>
“Human Dog!” Kezlat snarled as he grabbed Raff’s hair, yanking his head back painfully. “You have no idea how close you are to death,” he hissed. “It would take but a word from me and my elemental will kill you instantly.”<br>
<br>
Raff’s voice was hoarse. “Still can’t to do your own dirty work, huh Kezlat?” He coughed. “So, how much do you still owe for your last resurrection? I bet daddy wasn’t very happy with you at all, was he?”<br>
<br>
Kezlat swore and slammed Raff’s face into the gravel of the road. “If I had the time, Human, I’d show you how well I do my dirty work, but I have a scroll to deliver.”<br>
<br>
Raff coughed again and lifted himself slowly to his arms. He could only open one eye, and through it, saw blood on the gravel below him. “What scroll are you talking about?” he asked weakly. He could hear Kezlat going through his backpack.<br>
<br>
“Don’t presume I am as stupid as you Human. I know very well what scroll you carry.” <br>
<br>
Raff heard Kezlat move toward him, and then saw the Dark Elf’s feet before him. “This scroll, fool,” Kezlat said as he squatted down in front of Raff. He grabbed Raff’s hair and pulled his head back roughly, causing Raff to grunt in pain. With his other hand he held out the scroll tube. Raff could see his reflection in the tube, but this time he could barely recognize his blood and gravel covered face. <br>
<br>
“This scroll will bring back much honor to house K’Rins!” Kezlat exclaimed. <br>
<br>
Kezlat shoved Raff’s face into the gravel again and stood up. “Thank you, my dear friend, for going through the trouble to get this for me,” he sneered as he walked away. “Oh, my!” he said brightly, then stopped and turned back to Raff. “I almost forgot! You should have a nice long rest, so you don’t get any silly ideas and try to get this scroll back.” He waved his hand and a guttural noise came from the elemental beside Raff. It floated to him and began clubbing Raff with its rocky fists.<br>
<br>
For Raff, darkness came before the sun was down.<br>
