<br>
“Brother, it is good to see you,” Kezlat smiled.<br>
<br>
Zalar looked up from the scroll he was studying, a dubious expression on his face. “Save the pleasantries for your dealings with the Koada’Dal, Kezlat.” He pushed a few stray hairs away from his face and narrowed his red eyes at his brother. “Do you have the scroll?” he said gruffly.<br>
<br>
Kezlat continued to smile. “Yes, brother, I do.” He held out the scroll case.<br>
<br>
“Good. I’ve learned all I need to learn from this one.” He reached out a hand toward Kezlat, his gaze returning to the scroll before him. “Give me the second half.”<br>
<br>
Kezlat pulled the cylinder away from his brother’s hand, tapping it lightly against the palm of his other hand. “I am wondering what you have said to master T’Rald, Zalar.” Zalar looked up slowly, his red eyes flashing anger. “I have heard rumors.” Kezlat continued. “Rumors that suggest you have neglected to mention my part in acquiring this scroll when you have spoken to our Masters.”<br>
<br>
Zalar narrowed his eyes. “What does it matter Kezlat? You are in my house, we share status and power equally.”<br>
<br>
Kezlat frowned in mock disappointment. “But, brother dear, you know as well as I do that it does not always work that way.”<br>
<br>
Zalar slammed his hands on his desk and stood, his face twitching in anger. “Foolish child!” he spit furiously. “I could destroy you with a wave of my hand!” He pounded his fist on his desk to emphasize his point. “Now give me the scroll before I prove it to you!”<br>
<br>
Kezlat smiled calmly and sat down in the chair opposite his brother’s desk. “Oh, I don’t think you will do such a thing brother,” he said with a half-chuckle. “Not when you do not know where the scroll is.” He twisted the top of the scroll case off and tossed the case onto the desk casually.<br>
<br>
Zalar snatched the case from his desk and looked inside. His eyes returned to Kezlat an instant later. His brother smiled brightly at his glare. He dropped the case back onto the desk and sat down slowly, considered the grinning Elf across the desk. Slowly a smile crept into Zalar’s face and he threw back his head and laughed. “Well, brother, perhaps you will one day earn the right to call yourself a K’Rins!” he said as he laughed. “Where is the scroll?”<br>
<br>
“It is in a safe place,” replied Kezlat. “And once I have been given the credit I deserve, it is all yours.”<br>
<br>
Zalar folded his arms, smiling. “Very well, brother. Let us go and see Master T’Rald.” He rose and moved to the door, opening it for his brother. “After you brother,” he said pleasantly.<br>
<br>
* * *<br>
<br>
Raff wakened with a groan and slowly pulled himself into a sitting position. His head was pounding insistently and when he took a ragged breath he coughed painfully. It hurt to breath. Running his hand along his face, he felt a mass of dried blood mixed with dirt, gravel and hair. He looked around for his backpack and saw it a few feet from him. Unable to summon the strength to stand, he pulled himself along the ground. Dragging his body the five feet to his pack.  Once there, he reached inside, looking for a flask of water. When he found one he rolled over onto his back and opened it. He took a small sip, swallowing with difficulty and then poured some water on his face, wincing in pain as the water washed away some of the dried blood and exposed his wounds to the air. He let his hand fall to the ground and drifted into blackness again.<br>
<br>
* * *<br>
<br>
“Master T’Rald, it is good of you to see us,” Zalar said as he bowed before T’Rald. Kezlat mimicked his brother, bowing in deep respect.<br>
<br>
T’Rald stood before them, his hands folded calmly at his waist. “I trust that you have good reason to disturb me?”<br>
<br>
Zalar licked his lips and straightened. “Yes Master. My brother and I have discovered an important piece of lore that will bring great power to the Dark Summoners.”<br>
<br>
T’Rald looked curious. “Indeed? What is this great power that you speak of Zalar?”<br>
<br>
“We have managed to obtain a copy of the second half of the new summoning spell our researchers have been working on.” Kezlat said, beating out Zalar.<br>
<br>
“And,” Zalar interrupted Kezlat, “I have mastered the spell in its entirety,” he said with obvious pride.<br>
<br>
“And what does this have to do with me, Zalar?”<br>
<br>
“We wish to demonstrate the power of this spell to you first, before any other Summoner, Master T’Rald. We wish to bring honor to you, as your students,” Zalar explained.<br>
<br>
Kezlat spoke up. “And Zalar will demonstrate this new spell tomorrow morning, for your satisfaction, if you wish Master.”<br>
<br>
T’Rald looked at both of them carefully, as if determining the level of truth in their proposal. “Where and when?” he asked.<br>
<br>
“Tomorrow at noon, Master,” Kezlat said. “In the commons, at the edge of our forest.”<br>
<br>
T’Rald nodded silently. “Very well. Tomorrow at noon, in the commons. I will be there.” He turned to leave and then paused. “I trust you will not waste my time,” he said, his voice threatening, then turned and walked away.<br>
<br>
Kezlat grinned at his brother. “Now, let us go get the scroll that will allow bring pride back to our name, good brother.” Kezlat walked away briskly.<br>
<br>
Zalar scowled and followed his brother silently.<br>
<br>
* * *<br>
<br>
Raff woke to a stabbing pain in his head. Bright sunlight stabbed into his open eye from the sun overhead. He lay on his back for a good twenty minutes, trying to remember where he was, and what he was doing lying on the side of a road. Slowly his memory sifted back into his consciousness and he struggled to get to his knees. He picked up a flask of water lying on the ground beside where he had been sleeping and drained what was left of it. Slowly, agonizingly, he lifted himself to his feet, his breath coming in painful gasps. Grimacing, he lifted his backpack onto his shoulders and looked down the road before him with one eye. Grunting in pain, he started walking toward the Nektulos forest.<br>
