</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uraffphoenixheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raff Phoenixheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#CC9900>(2/12/01 5:24:01 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   School Days 11</span><hr size=1> School Days 11<br>
<br>
Kezlat paced nervously. “Do you have it Zalar?” he asked impatiently.<br>
<br>
“Shut up Kezlat,” Zalar growled. “I cannot concentrate with your childish gibbering” He was sitting cross-legged on the ground, staring at a large scroll in his lap.<br>
<br>
Kezlat looked at the sky nervously. By his estimation it was nearly noon. T’Rald would be coming very soon. He continued pacing back and forth, working his hands nervously as he did. He muttered something incoherently to himself.<br>
<br>
Abruptly Zalar rolled up the scroll and stood up. “I am done,” he announced.<br>
<br>
“Are you sure, brother? Do you know it for sure?”<br>
<br>
“Kezlat, do not anger me. I am in an excellent mood this day, and I do not wish to spend my time throttling you.” He looked at the sun, glowing hotly in the sky. “Master T’Rald should be here any moment,” he said thoughtfully.<br>
<br>
Kezlat grinned evilly. “Yes! And soon the house of K’Rins will rise to its proper place of power!” His eyes were distant as he fantasized about their future. He was snapped out of his reverie by Zalar’s announcement.<br>
<br>
“Here he comes Kezlat. Regain your wits. He turned toward his brother and snarled, “And this time, do not speak!”<br>
<br>
Kezlat scowled at his brother, but remained silent. Zalar waved his hand at the two figures approaching. A few moments later T’Rald and another Dark Elf arrived. Zalar and Kezlat bowed deeply before them.<br>
<br>
“Master T’Rald, how pleasant to see you,” Zalar said. “I trust your trip did not take too long?”<br>
<br>
T’Rald waved his hand dismissively. “Fuulik here was generous enough to teleport me nearby, thus my walk was short. However, the greatest threat to my time is you and your demonstration. I trust you are ready, and I will not be kept waiting with idle talk.”<br>
<br>
Zalar bowed again and said “I am ready Master, and I believe you will be impressed with the power of this spell.”<br>
<br>
T’Rald raised an eyebrow at Zalar. “Indeed? What is it that you plan to accomplish with this spell?”<br>
<br>
“We magicians are considered by all to be the masters of summoning,” he said as he swept his arm at the sky with a flourish. “But our summoning is limited in many ways. For instance, we are able to summon only four types of elementals to command.” He paused and held up a finger. “But now, I have the power to summon any creature I choose, and become its master instantly!”<br>
<br>
T’Rald glanced at Fuulik and shrugged. “Very well, Zalar, please demonstrate for us.”<br>
<br>
Zalar nodded and held his hands out from his sides. “Now I shall call upon a great beast of the air, the griffon, and, if one is near, it shall become mine to command!” He closed his eyes and was still for a moment, as if in concentration. Then he began to move his hands slowly. Lines of living magic, balls of colored light, began to coalesce around his hands and flow into his body, emanating in a circular pattern around him.<br>
<br>
Kezlat looked on, a broad grin on his face.<br>
<br>
* * *<br>
Raff moaned painfully as he gingerly pulled his backpack off his right arm. His face was a purple swollen mass of bruises, caked with dried blood. Wearily, he poured water into a basin and dipped a cloth into it. He began dabbing the cloth to his face, watching carefully in a mirror on his nightstand. His eye was swollen shut, and ached painfully. “Why is it,” he said to no one in particular, “that even when I’ve been sober for years, I still manage to get beat up?” He rinsed the cloth in the basin and placed it on the rim where it could dry properly, then carefully removed his tunic and breaches. After he replaced them with clean clothes, he took the scroll he’d copied in his hand and left his tiny room, heading toward Master T’Rald’s offices.<br>
<br>
The trip to T’Rald’s offices was a short one, from Raff’s small apartment in the dormitories. Three flights of stairs and one short passage later found him standing outside T’Rald’s office. Even though he was a powerful magician and a highly respected teacher, T’Rald preferred to work out of a small office near the campus. Raff had heard that his residence was extraordinarily opulent and more like a mansion than a house, but he’d never been near it.<br>
<br>
“Master T’Rald is not in his office at this time,” a younger female Teir’Dal said as Raff entered. She smiled pleasantly, and Raff couldn’t help pondering the benefit of wealth and power in the Dark Elf society. Her clothes, if they could be called that, barely covered the essential areas.<br>
<br>
“When do you expect him to return?” Raff asked.<br>
<br>
“He said he would be back within the hour,” she replied. “If you wait here, though, I can let him know you’re here when he returns.” She smiled again and shifted her hips seductively. “Who should I say is calling on him?”<br>
<br>
“Raff. I am a student of his.”<br>
<br>
She smiled again. “Oh yes, Raff, I have heard about you.” She tilted her head slightly and giggled. “Does your face always look like that?”<br>
<br>
Raff sat down wearily, wondering how unpleasant his wait would be.<br>
<br>
* * *<br>
<br>
Zalar was surrounded by swirling strands of liquid light – the living form of a spell as it undulated around his body. At once all the glowing balls and wisps of light entered him and his body shimmered amidst a bright glow. The glow pulsed  and then ebbed. Instantly a massive creature, half lion with the wings and head of a bird appeared before him. It flapped its powerful wings, forcing a massive blast of air at the four Dark Elves. From a beak larger than a human head came a shrill piercing cry that nearly deafened Zalar as he stood directly in front of the beast. He turned his back to the griffon and bowed in triumph. “And, now you know the true power of this spell,” he shouted, barely audible over the griffon’s squawking and the drum of its wings.<br>
<br>
Kezlat moved beside his brother, his face etched with obvious pride. Zalar looked at his brother and raised his hand to place it on Kezlat’s shoulder. It never made it to his shoulder.<br>
<br>
With a horrible screech the griffon grasped Zalar’s forearm in its beak and shook its head violently. The sickening crack of breaking bones pulled Kezlat out of his reverie and he turned in time to see his brother’s arm dangling lifeless at his side as the huge beast landed on the Elf, knocking him to the ground, its powerful talons deeply embedded in the Dark Elf’s shoulders. Zalar screamed until the griffon grasped his neck in its powerful beak, crushing it. Kezlat watched in horror as the creature strained its powerful muscles and pulled up on his brother’s head, ripping it from the Elf’s body like a raven feeding on a dead animal. Kezlat screamed and ran at the griffon, blind with rage. It moved with amazing speed, considering its size, and gored him with its claws, ripping a deep, bloody gash across his chest from his neck to his groin. Kezlat fell unconscious as the bird grasped him in its beak.<br>
<br>
Once Kezlat was dead, the bird turned in the air to face the remaining two Dark Elves. The time it had taken the bird to kill the two brothers was enough time for Master T’Rald and Fuulik to prepare themselves. T’Rald had summoned an elemental and ordered it to attack the griffon. Once it had engaged, Fuulik began to draw upon the immense magical powers at his disposal and struck the bird moments later with an intensely cold blast of magical ice. The creature fell within seconds.<br>
<br>
T’Rald and Fuulik walked up to the two dead brothers and determined that Kezlat was dead. His brother didn’t require any confirmation greater than his head lying five feet away from his body. T’Rald shook his head and frowned. “Thus the way of fools is a road well traveled,” he said quietly. Fuulik also shook his head.<br>
<br>
“They will be resurrected?” he asked.<br>
<br>
T’Rald nodded. “Yes, their family has a small amount of wealth.”<br>
<br>
“Should we carry the bodies back to Neriak then?”<br>
<br>
T’Rald shook his head. “No. Let them walk here and learn a lesson.” He looked thoughtful. “Although, I believe these two do not learn with any rapidity whatsoever.”<br>
<br>
Fuulik laughed. “Shall we return then?”<br>
<br>
“I do not see any reason to remain here,” T’Rald said, shrugging slightly.<br>
<br>
Fuulik started casting a portal spell to return the two to the Nektulos forest.<br>
