<br>
“So,” the young Dark Elf asked, kneeling at Raff’s feet, “is it true what they say about older humans?”<br>
<br>
Raff frowned at the young Elf. “You mean that we get gray hair?” he asked. <br>
<br>
She giggled. “No silly!” She ran a finger down Raff’s arm lightly and lowered her voice. “I’ve heard that you humans get more durable.”<br>
<br>
Raff looked at her finger on his arm. “What on Norrath are you talking about?” He folded his arms, putting an end to her touches.<br>
<br>
She pouted teasingly. “I heard you humans can last longer, you know, in bed, as you get older.” She lowered her head and looked at him from behind veiled eyes. “Is it true?”<br>
<br>
Raff groaned internally. “Yes, of course it’s true,” Raff said confidently. “In fact, most of us charge more as we age.”<br>
<br>
“Charge more?” the girl asked, the sultry tones in her voice instantly gone.<br>
<br>
“Yep,” Raff answered matter-of-factly. “Actually, we often charge more for younger people too. I would have to charge someone as young as you quite a bit for any sexual services.”<br>
<br>
Her eyes grew wide, and then narrowed. “You would charge me?” she said in disbelief. “You would charge me?” she repeated, louder.<br>
<br>
“Well yes,” Raff said with mock surprise. “What did you think?”<br>
<br>
“What did I think?” she sputtered and stood angrily. “How dare you!” She stomped back to her desk in the corner of the room. “Just for that,” she said flippantly over her shoulder, “I’ve just doubled my price, for you!”<br>
<br>
Raff looked at her, his face frozen in astonishment. “You mean you wanted me to pay you? Oh well, I’m sorry,” he said slowly, emphasizing the words, “I just assumed, since I’m an older human, that you’d be wanting to hire me.” He paused, as if considering. “Well, I suppose, also because of your looks.”<br>
<br>
“What about my looks?” she spat, her eyes narrowing in anger.<br>
<br>
“Oh, nothing,” Raff said off-handedly. “Just forget I said anything.”<br>
<br>
She scowled at him furiously. “What about my looks, human?”<br>
<br>
The door opened before Raff could respond.<br>
<br>
“Cyrindl,” Master T’Rald said as he entered the room. “Are you fighting with my students again?”<br>
<br>
The girl’s demeanor changed instantly, going from an aggressive, angry woman, to a meek child. “No Master,” she said as she lowered her head, averting her eyes from T’Rald. “We were just having a … a discussion about… about hate.” She looked over at Raff, her eyes flashing angrily. “Raff is here to see you.”<br>
<br>
T’Rald glanced at Raff, a small smile forming on his lips. “Raff. What brings you here to see me?”<br>
<br>
“A small matter you might be interested in Master,” Raff said bowing deeply.<br>
<br>
“Indeed? Well then, come into my office,” he said, gesturing to the other door in the small room.<br>
<br>
Raff stood up and followed T’Rald into his office. After he closed the door, he glanced around while Master T’Rald took a seat behind a large wooden desk. The room was opulently appointed, with elaborately carved polished wood bookshelves on all four walls. Raff easily recognized many common symbols of Innoruuk and the religion of Hate carved into the bookshelves. T’Rald indicated a large leather chair in front of the desk with his hand. “Sit, Raff.”<br>
<br>
Raff sat down and wondered if he’d be able to leave it, considering how easily his body sunk into its soft cushions. The door opened and Cyrindl entered carrying a small tray with two glasses of brandy. She placed them both on T’Rald’s desk and left silently. T’Rald watched her appreciatively as she left.<br>
<br>
“She is short on brains, but long on legs, is she not?” T’Rald asked.<br>
<br>
“I’ve seen more intelligent spiders,” Raff replied.<br>
<br>
T’Rald laughed. “And I suppose they are also long on leg, are they not?”<br>
<br>
Raff laughed lightly. “Yes, I suppose they are.”<br>
<br>
T’Rald reached for one of the glasses on the desk, nodding toward Raff, indicating he should do the same. He took a long sip and returned the glass to the desk. T’Rald looked at Raff’s glass. “Is there something wrong with my brandy?”<br>
<br>
“Although I’m sure your brandy is excellent, Master, I do not drink.”<br>
<br>
T’Rald pursed his lips, examining the human carefully. “Well then, Raff. What was it you wished to speak to me about?”<br>
<br>
Raff thought for a moment, and then said, “I’ve managed to obtain a new magic spell from the Freeport Academy of Arcane Science. I’m not skilled enough to interpret it completely, but, I understand that it allows the caster to summon another creature to control.”<br>
<br>
T’Rald frowned. “It doesn’t work Raff.”<br>
<br>
Raff blinked. “Pardon, Master? It doesn’t work? But… how could you know?”<br>
<br>
“I have seen the spell being cast, Raff. Not more than one hour ago, I witnessed Zalar casting this spell you speak of.” He narrowed his eyes and reached for the glass of brandy. “It failed somewhat spectacularly.”<br>
<br>
Raff shook his head, puzzled. “That doesn’t make any sense … I just got the spell two days before. I’m the only one who has it, except …” Raff’s eyes grew wide and a smile began to creep into his bruised face. “Master, does this have anything to do with Kezlat?” He asked.<br>
<br>
T’Rald tilted his head to the side, a curious expression on his face. “Yes Raff. He was there. Zalar, the magician who demonstrated the spell, is Kezlat’s older brother.”<br>
<br>
Raff’s smile had spread into a wide grin. “What was the, uh… outcome of the casting?”<br>
<br>
T’Rald raised an eyebrow at Raff. “As I said, it failed somewhat spectacularly: Zalar tried to summon a griffon in the commons. He succeeded in the summons, but failed in the control. The griffon destroyed him, and his brother before we could kill it.” <br>
<br>
He paused as Raff exploded in laughter, nearly falling from his chair. <br>
<br>
“There appears to be more to this than your simple rivalry with Kezlat,” T’Rald said. “Explain Raff.”<br>
<br>
Raff tried to control himself, gasping for air in between waves of laughter. Slowly he managed to calm himself enough to talk, but he was still giggling in between words. “Kezlat stole that scroll from me, Master,” he laughed. “He attacked me on the way back from Freeport and took the scroll from me.” He chuckled again and then wiped a tear from his eye.<br>
<br>
T’Rald looked at Raff, mildly irritated. “That would explain the bruises on your face. Why were you carrying a faulty scroll, and why would you suggest I would be interested in such a dangerous spell?”<br>
<br>
Raff waved his hand to indicate T’Rald was misunderstanding. “The Academy had deliberately tampered with the scroll so that we wouldn’t be able to use it properly.” He slapped his hand on the arm of the chair and he laughed again. “Kezlat is so stupid he just took the wrong scroll!”<br>
<br>
“The wrong scroll?” T’Rald said, his voice terse. “My patience is quickly coming to an end. Explain clearly.”<br>
<br>
Raff  quickly calmed himself and explained how he’d made a copy of the scroll so that he would have a copy for himself in the future, how the Academy had sought to trade information with the Dark Summoners, and how Kezlat had taken the incorrect scroll. He showed T’Rald the scroll he’d copied and explained that it was taken from the original scroll. Finally he told T’Rald about the deal he’d made with the Academy for the first half of the scroll. When he was done he was still smiling and T’Rald was leaning over the copied scroll on his desk.<br>
<br>
“Raff, you never cease to surprise me,” T’Rald said, a small smile on his face. “Then again, neither does Kezlat.”<br>
<br>
“I hope it can be used to aid our research, Master,” Raff said obsequiously.<br>
<br>
There is one difficulty, however” T’Rald said.<br>
<br>
“Yes?”<br>
<br>
T’Rald sat down behind his desk again. “You have a deal with the Academy to return a scroll for payment,” T’Rald reminded him.<br>
<br>
“Oh, yes, I do,” Raff answered. “I have a suggestion for that as well.”<br>
<br>
“Somehow, Raff, I am not surprised. What do you suggest? Keep in mind, of course, that I have no wish to aid the Academy in any way, and that I owe you nothing.”<br>
<br>
Raff nodded. “I would like to return to Freeport with a copy of the first half of the spell and claim my thousand platinum. However, I’d like to give them a subtly inaccurate scroll, something that will require them to spend a great deal of time solving.” He grinned to himself. “Maybe something that would attack gnomes on sight.”<br>
<br>
“Pardon?” T’Rald asked.<br>
<br>
“Nothing” Raff said, laughing.<br>
<br>
“Well Raff, this is the situation.” T’Rald rolled up the scroll carefully and stood. “I have no need whatsoever to provide you with a way to make one thousand platinum. As far as my concerns go, you do not factor into them.” He looked at Raff, intensity in his eyes. “What I do wish, however, is to thwart any attempts the Academy makes at researching this spell, and I believe that can be accomplished best by falsely leading them down the wrong path with a cunning diversion.” He indicated at Raff with the rolled up scroll. “This scroll,” he said confidently, “it just that diversion.” He moved to the door and opened it. “Come back in two days and I shall have a modified copy of the first half of the scroll ready for you to return to Academy.”<br>
<br>
Raff rose quietly. “Of course, Master.” He bowed and left quietly, knowing instinctively it was time for him to leave. <br>
<br>
Just as Raff reached the outer door, T’Rald said, “Oh, and Raff?”<br>
<br>
Raff turned and said “Yes, Master?”<br>
<br>
T’Rald smiled. “I am sure the costs for the resurrection of Zalar and Kezlat will be extremely high.” He paused. “Perhaps higher than normally is the case.”<br>
<br>
Raff smiled in return. “My thanks, Master T’Rald.” <br>
<br>
He left the building and walked back to his room, his face hurting whenever he smiled. His face hurt for the rest of the day.<br>
