Raff held the bag of platinum coins in his hand, surprised how much the thousand small coins weighed. He tied the pouch carefully on his belt, inside his tunic so that it wouldn’t be ‘borrowed’ by any passing thieves. He bowed to Tara and said, “I believe this means our business is complete Tara.”<br>
<br>
Tara moved from behind her desk and approached Raff. “On behalf of the Academy, Raff, I thank you for you help in this matter. Perhaps this will form new lines of communication between Neriak and Freeport,” Tara said, smiling. “You have done both guilds a service this day, Raff.” She leaned back against her desk,  half sitting on the front of it. A few moments earlier she had taken the scroll from Raff and passed it to Konkir for immediate study.<br>
<br>
Raff bowed. “I am merely a messenger, Tara.”<br>
<br>
Tara laughed. “You are anything but a merely a messenger, Raff. Don’t ever forget that.” She paused, watching Raff carefully.  “What are your plans for the money Raff? That’s more money than most people see in a lifetime.”<br>
<br>
Raff looked down thoughtfully and thought a moment before looking up at Tara. He spoke quietly. “Tara, I have seen far too much hate in the last while – more than you can imagine, I’m sure. For a while, tonight, I plan on balancing some of the hate in my life, with some kindness.”<br>
<br>
Tara smiled again. “Going to buy something nice for a lady friend, Raff?” For a moment Raff thought she sounded a bit disappointed.<br>
<br>
Raff nodded slowly, a far away look in his eyes. “Yes Tara. A lady friend.” he said. “Something like that.”<br>
<br>
* * *<br>
<br>
Raff stood quietly in the dark alley, listening to the light pattering of rain on the rooftops overhead. He was sheltered for the moment, standing under the eaves of a large house. He watched the water running down the dirty streets, swirling along the cobblestones on its way to the sewer, carrying away all the dirt and grime. Dirt and grime, he thought. How much dirt and grime have I sat in – no wallowed in - over the last decade? How many times have I wished I could just be washed clean, like these streets? He stepped out from under the eaves and turned his face to the sky, allowing the rain to splash against his skin. Through the rainy mist he could see the moon, risen fully in the sky. He wiped his face with the back of his sleeve slowly and sighed. Time to wash away some grime, he said to himself as he stepped out of the alley.<br>
<br>
He walked purposefully in the rain toward a large house near the docks. As he approached the tall building the sound of laughter and revelry drifted through the white noise of the falling rain. Standing outside the door to the house was a large burly man with thick black hair. His face was heavily scarred, including one that ran from above his right eyebrow to his jaw line, leaving a dark empty hole where is eye used to be. He turned his remaining eye to Raff and spoke gruffly. <br>
<br>
“Whatcha want? You looking for a good time?”<br>
<br>
Raff nodded silently.<br>
<br>
“You got money?”<br>
<br>
Raff nodded again and shook his belt pouch to emphasize the point.<br>
<br>
“OK, you get in.” he said, motioning with his head toward the door behind him. As Raff walked past him, the large man grabbed Raff’s shoulder in a meaty grasp. “I don’t want no trouble outta you. You hear?”<br>
<br>
“There’ll be no trouble from me, friend. You can count on it.” The other man grunted and removed his hand from Raff’s shoulder.<br>
<br>
The sounds of laugher and clinking of glasses were much louder as Raff walked up the narrow staircase to the main floor of the old building. Interspersed with the party noises Raff heard the unmistakable cries of passion, making the nature of the building obvious to anyone who approached it. He reached the landing and entered a doorway into a crowded room. Before he walked two feet inside the room a scantily clad woman draped herself over him, her hand roaming across his chest.<br>
<br>
“Hey there fella,” she slurred, obviously drunk. “Looking for a good time?” She was fairly tall for a human, and Raff thought her blonde hair suggested some high elf in her past. Her breath reeked of alcohol, and from her behavior, it looked like she’d been drinking for a long while. <br>
<br>
Raff pressed a platinum coin in the palm of her hand and said, “Yes, sweetheart, but not from you, I’m afraid. I’m looking for someone in particular.” He frowned in mock sadness and she responded in kind.<br>
<br>
“What? Am I ugly?” she asked, her eyelashes batting.<br>
<br>
“No, gorgeous, you’re just too good looking for someone like me.” He smiled, supporting her as she staggered. “I’m looking for Melissa. Is she around?”<br>
<br>
“Oooooh,” she squealed. “Like ‘em young, do ya?”<br>
<br>
Raff forced himself to smile even though his gut twisted at her suggestion. “Something like that beautiful. Where is she?”<br>
<br>
“You don’t need her!” she said putting her hand on his chest. “You won’t get anything out of her! She’s got no experience.” She ran a finger down his chest seductively. “You need a woman not a girl,” she slurred.<br>
<br>
Raff took her hand in his and held up another platinum coin. He pulled it away as she reached for it. “This is yours if you take me to her.”<br>
<br>
She smiled brightly. “OK, hon, follow me.” She turned and walked to a banister staircase. Her attempts to be seductive combined with her intoxication, making the walk look ridiculous, and Raff found it hard to keep from laughing. He followed her up the staircase, stopping to support her twice on the way up. At the top of the stairs she turned and walked down a short hallway to a closed door.  From the sounds around him, Raff thought business was good that night.<br>
<br>
“Here ya are sugar.” She smiled at him again. “This is her bedroom. She’s been pretty busy tonight, though, so you might need to wake her.”<br>
<br>
“Thank you,” Raff said as he gave her the second platinum. She took it and stumbled past him to the stairs.<br>
<br>
“If you change yer mind, I’ll be downstairs big spender,” she called to him as she started down the stairs.<br>
<br>
Raff waited until she was gone and then took a deep breath. Carefully he opened the door to Melissa’s room, trying to be quiet, and slipped inside.<br>
<br>
It took a few minutes for his eyes to adjust to the dim lighting inside the room, but years in the blackness of Neriak had heightened his night vision, and the light from the full moon shining through the window allowed him to see well enough. The room was bare except for a dresser, a night table, and a fairly large bed. He could make out the shape of a young girl under the covers, and he moved stealthily toward her. Before he dropped off the bag of money, he had to be sure that the girl was who he thought she was. He had managed to watch her over the last few days, and by talking to some of the girls around this house, he managed to find out enough to convince him this was the girl he was looking for. His questions had confirmed that her father had died about five years ago while attacking the man who had fired him from the bakery the day before. The bakery owner had also died in the fight, and the following day the owner’s son had avenged his father by killing the girl’s mother. Once the girl had recovered from the brutal beating she’d received from the son, she started a new life living on the streets. A few years later she was convinced to enter prostitution. The thought of someone so young turning to the life of a street prostitute sickened Raff to his core.<br>
<br>
 When he reached her bedside, he looked down at her. She was lying on her back, an arm across her chest. Her long blonde hair cascaded down the pillow and off the bed. Raff gasped in surprise when he looked at her face. She looked to be about 12 years old. Has it been that long? He asked himself. He looked to her right hand and saw, glimmering in the moonlight, a silver ring. Raff didn’t have to look at it to know it had the markings of Erolisi Marr on it. For years it had been his most prized possession. He choked back a sudden cry and pressed his hand to his mouth as his body shook with an uncontrollable shudder. His eyes flooded with tears and he reached out with his other hand to steady himself against the night table. He slowly sank to his knees and covered his head with his hands. He knelt there many long minutes, the girl a footstep away from him, sleeping peacefully. The moonlight silhouetted his body, casting a shadow on the floor, as he stayed there, hunched tightly, tears running down his face quietly. Years of repressed sadness, anger and bitterness leapt forward to consume him. He rocked on his knees slightly as his body trembled with memories long sealed away in the fortress of his heart.<br>
<br>
With immense difficulty he managed to remain quiet, even though he continued to cry for over five minutes. Finally, he managed to calm himself enough to wipe his face and open his eyes. He moved to his feet slowly, a man four times his age, and retrieved the large bag of platinum from under his tunic. He placed it on the bed beside the young girl carefully, not wanting to wake her. Then he removed a note from his belt and placed it on the nightstand. Breathing deeply, he walked quietly out of the room and locked the door from the inside before closing it.<br>
<br>
He stood out in the dark hallway wiping his face carefully on his tunic to remove all trace of his tears before heading downstairs. When he reached the bottom of the stairs he made his way through the crowded room, looking for his earlier assistant. She saw him before he saw her, and pushed her way to meet him.<br>
<br>
“That couldn’t have been enough time for a strong man like you!” she said seductively.<br>
<br>
Raff turned and looked at her with dark eyes, utterly devoid of mirth. “Listen carefully,” he said. “I need you to do something very, very important for me. If you do it, I will pay you ten platinum for your work. Do you understand?”<br>
<br>
The seriousness in Raff’s look made the woman pause before she responded with her usual suggestive answer. Raff knew fully well that ten platinum was more money than the woman would make in a month.<br>
<br>
“Yes, I understand. What do I have to do?” she asked meekly. Raff was impressed by how fast she seemed to sober up.<br>
<br>
“I do not want Melissa disturbed tonight, for any reason.” He stared at her with eyes that suggested she didn’t have a choice in the matter. “Do you understand?” He asked again.<br>
<br>
“Y… yes, I understand,” she said, her voice timid.<br>
<br>
“Good,” he said. “Here are three platinum coins. You will find me tomorrow at the Jade Tiger Inn. When you come tomorrow, I will give you the other seven coins.” He started to give her the three coins, but pulled his hand back as she reached for them. “There’s one more thing,” he added. She nodded silently. “You are to under no circumstances, ever let her know that you saw me, or who I am. Is that clear?” When she nodded again he gave her the three coins. “Good. I will expect to see you tomorrow morning then.” She turned to leave and he put his hand to her chin, turning her head toward him and glared at her intensely. “And one other thing. If I ever find out you haven’t followed my orders, I will kill you without a thought. Understand?”<br>
<br>
The woman swallowed and nodded.<br>
<br>
“Good,” he said, and left without another word.<br>
<br>
Outside the rain was falling harder now, and the water was pooling in parts of the streets where traffic had worn the stones down more than others. As Raff trudged through the wet alleys, his head was down. He was watching the water as it ran along the stones, carrying away the dirt -washing the streets clean.<br>
